A)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1960-61 Norwegian Main League}}\n[[Category:Eliteserien seasons]]\n[[Category:1960\u201361 in European association football leagues|Norway]]\n[[Category:1960 in Norwegian football]]\n[[Category:1961 in Norwegian football]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1960%E2%80%9361_Norwegian_Main_League"}
{"title_page": "Spectre (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 James Bond film by Sam Mendes}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Spectre\n| image          = spectre poster.jpg\n| alt            = James Bond, holding a gun and standing next to Dr. Swann in front of a masked man, with the film's title and credits\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Sam Mendes]]\n| producer       = {{unbulleted list|[[Michael G. Wilson]]|[[Barbara Broccoli]]}}\n| screenplay     = {{plainlist|\n* [[John Logan (writer)|John Logan]]\n* [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade|Neal Purvis<br>Robert Wade]]\n* [[Jez Butterworth]]\n}}\n| story          = {{plainlist|\n* John Logan\n* Neal Purvis\n* Robert Wade\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]]|[[Ian Fleming]]}}\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[Daniel Craig]]|[[Christoph Waltz]]||[[L\u00e9a Seydoux]]|[[Ben Whishaw]]|[[Naomie Harris]]|[[Dave Bautista]]|[[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]]|[[Monica Bellucci]]|[[Ralph Fiennes]]}}\n| music          = [[Thomas Newman]]\n| cinematography = [[Hoyte van Hoytema]]\n| editing        = [[Lee Smith (editor)|Lee Smith]]\n| studio         = {{unbulleted list|[[Eon Productions]]|[[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures]]|[[Columbia Pictures]]<ref name=\"catalog.afi.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/70719?sid=eee64a3c-4b88-4649-bb50-c42cdcef0998&sr=1.479148&cp=1&pos=0 | title=AFI&#124;Catalog}}</ref>}}\n| distributor    = [[Sony Pictures Releasing]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2015|10|26|United Kingdom|2015|11|6|United States}}<!-- DO NOT ADD ANY OTHER DATES&nbsp;\u2014 SEE WP:FILMRELEASE -->\n| runtime        = 148 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 147:58--><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/spectre-film |title=''Spectre'' (12A) |work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105102751/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/spectre-film |archivedate= 5 November 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n| country        = {{plainlist|\n* United Kingdom\n* United States<ref name=bfi>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5632a9b434430 |title=SPECTRE (2015) |work=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=29 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160507100155/http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/5632a9b434430 |archivedate= 7 May 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n}}\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $245\u2013300 <!--THIS IS ONLY FOR PRODUCTION. YES IT IS UPWARDS OF $350 WITH PROMOTION, BUT THATS NOT FOR HERE-->million{{refn|name=SPECTRE bugdet|group=N|The official production budget for ''Spectre'' has been debated. Estimates range from $245\u2013250<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/2015_film_study_v5_WEB.pdf|title=2015 Feature Film Study|last=FilmL.A.|first=|date=15 June 2016|page=25|accessdate=17 June 2018|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-preview-spectre-peanuts-836282 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qDBb3xKV |archivedate= 4 May 2017 |title=Box-Office Preview: ''Spectre'' and ''Peanuts Movie'' to the Rescue |author=Pamela McClintock |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=4 November 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"budget2\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-the-peanuts-movie-james-bond-box-office-1201610575/ |title=''Spectre'' Now Targeting $73M to $74M Opening; ''The Peanuts Movie'' Cracking $40M-$45M&nbsp;\u2013 Updated |author=Anthony D'Alessandro |publisher=Deadline.com |date=7 November 2015 |accessdate=8 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107115522/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-the-peanuts-movie-james-bond-box-office-1201610575/ |archivedate= 7 November 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/box-office/spectre-box-office-1201633311/ |title=Box Office: ''Spectre'' Needs to Make $650 Million to Break Even |author=Brent Lang |work=Variety |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=8 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108072608/http://variety.com/2015/film/box-office/spectre-box-office-1201633311/ |archivedate= 8 November 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/spectre-the-peanuts-movie-give-box-office-a-welcome-boost-1447023829 |title=''Spectre'', ''The Peanuts Movie'' Give Box Office a Welcome Boost |author=Ben Fritz |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=8 November 2015 |accessdate=10 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109152512/http://www.wsj.com/articles/spectre-the-peanuts-movie-give-box-office-a-welcome-boost-1447023829 |archivedate= 9 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> to as high as $300\u2013350 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/10/21/why-james-bond-like-mission-impossible-is-a-bullet-proof-franchise/ |title='Spectre' Doesn't Need To Top 'Skyfall' Because 'James Bond' Is A Bullet-Proof Franchise |author=Scott Mendelson |work=Forbes |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=8 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030103627/http://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/10/21/why-james-bond-like-mission-impossible-is-a-bullet-proof-franchise/ |archivedate=30 October 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/spectre-movie-numbers-daniel-craig-salary-film-budget-james-bond-theme-tune-sales-1525412 |title=Spectre movie in numbers: Daniel Craig salary, film budget and James Bond theme tune sales |author=Alicia Adejobi |work=International Business Times |date=25 October 2015 |accessdate=8 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115073422/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/spectre-movie-numbers-daniel-craig-salary-film-budget-james-bond-theme-tune-sales-1525412 |archivedate=15 November 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Spectre#tab=summary|title=Spectre (2015) |work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> The $350 million figure also incorporates the $100 million marketing budget.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-profit-box-office-skyfall-james-bond-franchise-1201615942/ |title=Even Shy of ''Skyfall'', ''Spectre'' Picked Up Sluggish Box Office; Will it Turn a Profit?&nbsp;\u2013 Monday Postmortem |author=Anthony D'Alessandro |publisher=Deadline.com |date=9 November 2015 |accessdate=11 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112183915/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-profit-box-office-skyfall-james-bond-franchise-1201615942/ |archivedate=12 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> $21.5 million was spent on television advertisements and a further $100 million was spent on promotion and advertising.<ref name=\"budget2\"/>}}\n| gross          = $880.7 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bond24.htm |title=Spectre (2015) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=21 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419085109/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bond24.htm |archivedate=19 April 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Spectre''''' is a 2015 [[spy film]] and the twenty-fourth in the [[List of James Bond films|''James Bond'' series]] produced by [[Eon Productions]] for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] and [[Columbia Pictures]]. It is the fourth film to feature [[Daniel Craig]] as the fictional [[MI6]] agent [[Portrayal of James Bond in film|James Bond]], and the second film in the series directed by [[Sam Mendes]] following ''[[Skyfall]].'' It was written by [[John Logan (writer)|John Logan]], [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade|Neal Purvis, Robert Wade]], and [[Jez Butterworth]]. It is the final ''James Bond'' film to be co-distributed by Columbia Pictures, as [[Universal Pictures]] will become the international distributor of its future films.\n\nThe story sees Bond pitted against the global criminal organisation [[SPECTRE|Spectre]] and their enigmatic leader [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld]] ([[Christoph Waltz]]), who plans to launch a national surveillance network to mastermind criminal activities across the globe. The film marks Spectre and Blofeld's first appearance in an Eon Productions film since 1971's ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]'';{{refn|name=SPECTRE reboot|group=N|Within the series' continuity, the version of [[SPECTRE|Spectre]] that appeared in ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]'' was written out of the timeline with the 2006 reboot of the franchise in ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'', making its appearance in ''Spectre'' its first in the new timeline.}} a character resembling Blofeld had previously appeared in the 1981 film, ''[[For Your Eyes Only (film)|For Your Eyes Only]]'', but, because of the [[Thunderball (novel)#Writing and copyright|''Thunderball'' controversy]], he is not named, nor is his face shown. Several [[List of recurring characters in the James Bond film series|''James Bond'' characters]], including [[M (James Bond)|M]], [[Q (James Bond)|Q]] and [[Miss Moneypenny|Eve Moneypenny]], return, with new additions [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]] as Dr. Madeleine Swann, [[Dave Bautista]] as Mr. Hinx, [[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]] as Max Denbigh and [[Monica Bellucci]] as Lucia Sciarra.\n\n''Spectre'' was filmed from December 2014 to July 2015 in Austria, the United Kingdom, Italy, Morocco and Mexico. The action scenes prioritised practical effects and stunts, while employing computer-generated imagery made by five different companies. ''Spectre'' was estimated to have cost around $245 million&mdash;with some sources listing it as high as $300 million&mdash;making it the most expensive Bond film and [[List of most expensive films|one of the most expensive films ever made]].\n\n''Spectre'' was released on 26 October 2015 in the United Kingdom\u201450 years after the release of ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'', 30 after ''[[A View to a Kill]]'', and 20 after ''[[GoldenEye]]''\u2014on the night of the world premiere at the London [[Royal Albert Hall]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/spectre-world-premiere-at-the-royal-albert-hall-london/ | title= Ikon London Magazine Coverage from the world premiere of Spectre | publisher= Ikon London Magazine | date=27 October 2015 | accessdate= 3 March 2018}}</ref> It was followed by a worldwide release, including [[IMAX]] screenings. It was released in the United States on 6 November. ''Spectre'' received mixed reviews from critics who praised the film's action sequences, cinematography, acting and musical score, though some criticism was aimed at the excessive runtime, screenplay and pacing. The theme song \"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\", performed and co-written by [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]], won an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Golden Globe]] for Best Original Song. ''Spectre'' grossed over $880 million worldwide, making it the [[2015 in film|sixth-highest-grossing film of 2015]] and the second-largest [[Inflation|unadjusted]] total for the series after ''Skyfall''.\n\nThe next film in the series, ''[[No Time to Die]]'', is to be released in November 2020, with Craig reprising his role for the final time and [[Cary Joji Fukunaga]] directing.\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- FILM PLOTS should be no more than 700 words, so please do not add to this summary unless you can keep the word count below that figure. -->\nA posthumous message from the previous [[M (James Bond)|M]] leads [[MI6]] agent James Bond to carry out an unauthorised mission in [[Mexico City]] on the [[Day of the Dead]], where he stops a terrorist bombing plot. Bond kills Marco Sciarra, the terrorist leader, and takes his ring, which is emblazoned with a stylised octopus.\n\nUpon his return to [[London]], Bond is suspended from field duty by [[Gareth Mallory]], the current M, who is engaged in a power struggle with Max Denbigh (whom Bond dubs \"C\"), the Director-General of the new, [[private intelligence agency|privately backed]] Joint Intelligence Service formed by a recent merger of [[MI5]] and MI6. C campaigns for Britain to join the global surveillance and intelligence initiative \"[[Five Eyes#Nine Eyes|Nine Eyes]]\", and uses his influence to close down the [[00 Agent|'00']] field agent section, which he believes is outdated.\n\nBond disobeys M's orders and travels to Rome to attend Sciarra's funeral. He saves and seduces Sciarra's widow, Lucia, who tells him Sciarra belonged to an organisation of businessmen with criminal and terrorist connections. Bond uses Sciarra's ring to infiltrate a meeting to select Sciarra's replacement, where he identifies the leader, Franz Oberhauser. After hearing Oberhauser give the order for the \"Pale King\" to be assassinated, Bond is pursued across the city by the organisation's assassin, Mr. Hinx. [[Miss Moneypenny|Eve Moneypenny]] informs Bond that the Pale King is [[Mr. White (James Bond)|Mr. White]], a former member of the organisation's subsidiary Quantum who had fallen afoul of Oberhauser. Bond asks her to investigate Oberhauser, who was presumed dead roughly twenty years earlier.\n\nBond locates White in [[Altaussee]], Austria, where he is dying of [[thallium poisoning]]. He tells Bond to find and protect his daughter, psychiatrist Dr. Madeleine Swann, who will take him to L'Am\u00e9ricain in order to locate Oberhauser; White then commits suicide. Bond confronts Swann and rescues her from Hinx and his forces. The pair meet [[Q (James Bond)|Q]], who links Oberhauser to Bond's previous missions, identifying [[Le Chiffre]], [[Dominic Greene (James Bond)|Dominic Greene]] and [[Raoul Silva]] as agents of the same organisation, which Swann identifies as [[SPECTRE|Spectre]].\n\nSwann takes Bond to L'Am\u00e9ricain, a hotel in [[Tangier]], and they discover that White left evidence directing them to Oberhauser's base at a crater in the [[Sahara]]. Taking a train to a remote station, Bond and Swann encounter Hinx, who gets ejected from the train in the ensuing fight, and are escorted to Oberhauser's base. Oberhauser reveals that Spectre has funded the Joint Intelligence Service while staging terrorist attacks around the world, creating a need for the Nine Eyes programme. In return, C will give Spectre unlimited access to intelligence gathered by Nine Eyes, allowing them to anticipate and counter-act investigations into their operations. Bond is tortured as Oberhauser discusses their shared history: after the younger Bond was orphaned, Oberhauser's father, Hannes, became his temporary guardian. Believing that Bond supplanted his role as son, Oberhauser killed his father, staged his own death, adopted the name [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld]] and went on to form Spectre and target Bond. Bond and Swann stun Blofeld by setting off an explosive wristwatch at his face, and the two escape to London to prevent Nine Eyes from going online.\n\nIn London, Bond and Swann meet M, [[Bill Tanner]], Q, and Moneypenny with the intention of arresting C. Swann and Bond are abducted separately by Spectre operatives, while the rest of the group proceed with the plan. After Q succeeds in preventing the Nine Eyes from going online, a struggle between M and C ends with C falling to his death. Bond is taken to the ruins of the old [[SIS Building|MI6 building]], scheduled for demolition after Silva's bombing.{{refn|group=N|As depicted in ''[[Skyfall]]''.}} Blofeld, still alive, but now scarred over his right eye, tells Bond that he must escape before explosives are detonated in three minutes' time, or die trying to save Swann. Bond finds Swann and they escape by boat as the building collapses. Bond shoots down Blofeld's helicopter, which crashes onto [[Westminster Bridge]]. As Blofeld crawls from the wreckage, Bond confronts him but rather than kill him, leaves him to be arrested by M, before leaving the bridge with Swann. \n\nThe next morning, Bond borrows the repaired [[Aston Martin DB5]] from Q and drives away with Swann.\n\n=== Vehicles featured ===\n*[[Aston Martin DB10]]\n\n* [[Jaguar C-X75]]\n* [[Aston Martin DB5]]\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Daniel Craig]] as [[James Bond filmography|James Bond]], agent 007. The director [[Sam Mendes]] has described Bond as being extremely focused in ''Spectre'', likening his new-found dedication to hunting.<ref name=\"on a mission\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/31654971/sam-mendes-spectre-about-bonds-childhood |title=Sam Mendes: ''Spectre'' about Bond's childhood |publisher=BBC Entertainment |date=27 February 2015 |accessdate=28 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150629233124/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/31654971/sam-mendes-spectre-about-bonds-childhood |archivedate=29 June 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n* [[Christoph Waltz]] as [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld]] (born Franz Oberhauser), Bond's nemesis and the mysterious mastermind behind [[SPECTRE]], as well as the puppeteer responsible for a series of recent events in Bond's life, stemming from a hatred for James due to their shared childhood.\n* [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]] as Dr. Madeleine Swann, a psychiatrist working at a private medical clinic in the [[Central Eastern Alps|Austrian Alps]],<ref name=emp0415>{{cite news|last1=Hewitt|first1=Chris|title=Bond is Back: Spectre|work=Empire|issue=April 2015|pages=60\u201371|date=26 February 2015}}</ref> and the daughter of [[List of James Bond villains#Eon Productions films|Mr. White]].<ref name=WhiteSwann>{{cite web|title=The Bond Women of Spectre|url=http://www.007.com/the-bond-women-of-spectre/|publisher=007.com|accessdate=27 August 2015|date=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Whishaw]] as [[Q (James Bond)|Q]], the MI6 quartermaster who outfits Bond with equipment for use in the field.\n* [[Naomie Harris]] as [[Miss Moneypenny|Eve Moneypenny]], a former agent who left the field to become M's assistant.\n* [[Dave Bautista]] as Mr. Hinx, Spectre's huge, muscle-bound assassin.\n* [[Andrew Scott (actor)|Andrew Scott]] as C (Max Denbigh), Head of the new Joint Intelligence Service, and an agent for Spectre, heavily involved with their plan to merge nine national intelligence agencies into the Nine Eyes Committee, thus allowing Spectre the power to take over the world.\n* [[Rory Kinnear]] as [[Bill Tanner]], the MI6 Chief of Staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/theatre/rory-kinnear-on-the-trial-spectre-and-always-being-asked-about-his-fathers-death-10322803.html |title=Rory Kinnear on The Trial, Spectre and always being asked about his father's death |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=16 June 2015 |accessdate=13 September 2015 |last=Nicol |first=Patricia |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151015164501/http://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/theatre/rory-kinnear-on-the-trial-spectre-and-always-being-asked-about-his-fathers-death-10322803.html |archivedate=15 October 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n* [[Jesper Christensen]] as Mr. White, a fugitive from MI6 and a former senior figure in Spectre's [[List of James Bond villains#Villainous organisations|Quantum]] subsidiary, as portrayed in ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'' and ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'',<ref name=\"Euroman.dk\">{{cite web|last1=Peter Nicolai |first1=Gudme Christensen |title=Jesper Christensen skal v\u00e6re James Bond-skurk for tredje gang |url=http://www.euroman.dk/kultur/jesper-christensen-skal-vare-james-bond-skurk-for-tredje-gang |website=Euroman |accessdate=4 December 2014 |date=4 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160616232419/http://www.euroman.dk/kultur/jesper-christensen-skal-vare-james-bond-skurk-for-tredje-gang/ |archivedate=16 June 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Empire-Christensen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/mr-white-will-return-spectre/ |title=Mr White Will Return In SPECTRE |author=Williams, Owen |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |date=5 December 2014 |accessdate=6 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305195416/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/mr-white-will-return-spectre/ |archivedate= 5 March 2016 |df= }}</ref> now dying from thallium poisoning after falling from Spectre's favour over his reservations relating to human trafficking.\n* [[Monica Bellucci]] as Lucia Sciarra, the wife of assassin Marco Sciarra.\n* [[Ralph Fiennes]] as [[M (James Bond)|M]] (Gareth Mallory), head of MI6.\n* [[Stephanie Sigman]] as Estrella, a Mexican agent who accompanies Bond on his mission to assassinate Marco Sciarra. In the video game ''James Bond: World of Espionage'', her full name is given as Estrella Luna.\n* Alessandro Cremona as Marco Sciarra,<ref name=\"cremona\"/> a Spectre agent whom Bond kills in the pre-title sequence of the movie.\n* [[Judi Dench]] as Mallory's predecessor M. She gave Bond her posthumous mission to him. This marks Judi Dench playing M for twenty years since ''[[GoldenEye]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-cameos-2015/ |title=The 16 best cameos of 2015 |first=James |last=White |work=Empire |date=14 December 2015 |accessdate=17 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218143524/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/best-cameos-2015/ |archivedate=18 December 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n===Pre-production===\nIn March 2013 Mendes said he would not return to direct the next film in the series, then known as ''Bond 24'';<ref name=\"noMendes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-21687612 |title=Sam Mendes \"won't direct\" next Bond |publisher=BBC News |date=6 March 2013 |accessdate=4 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724081240/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-21687612 |archivedate=24 July 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"EmpireMendes\">{{cite web|last=de Semlyen |first=Phil |url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/news/sam-mendes-direct-bond-24/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6q1G9V4sX |archivedate=26 April 2017 |title=Sam Mendes Won't Direct Bond 24 |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |date=6 March 2013 |accessdate=4 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> he later recanted and announced that he would return, as he found the script and the plans for the long-term future of the franchise appealing.<ref>{{cite news|title=''Spectre'': Sam Mendes hints at 'more mischief' in new James Bond film|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-30328726/mendes-more-mischief-in-spectre|first=Lizo|last=Mzimba|publisher=BBC News |date=4 December 2014|accessdate=6 December 2014}}</ref> [[Nicolas Winding Refn]] would later reveal that he turned down an offer to direct the movie.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nordine |first=Michael |title=Why Nicolas Winding Refn Says He Turned Down 'Spectre' |date=3 July 2016 |publisher=[[Indiewire]] |url=http://www.indiewire.com/2016/07/nicolas-winding-refn-spectre-the-neon-demon-the-avenging-silence-1201702305/ |accessdate=15 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220180255/http://www.indiewire.com/2016/07/nicolas-winding-refn-spectre-the-neon-demon-the-avenging-silence-1201702305/ |archivedate=20 December 2016 |df= }}</ref> In directing ''Skyfall'' and ''Spectre'', Mendes became the first director to oversee two successive ''Bond'' films since [[John Glen (director)|John Glen]] directed five consecutive films, ending with ''[[The Living Daylights]]'' and ''[[Licence to Kill]]'' in 1987 and 1989.<ref name=\"MendesLogan to return\"/> [[Dennis Gassner]] returned as the film's production designer,<ref name=\"cast & crew\"/> while cinematographer [[Hoyte van Hoytema]] took over from [[Roger Deakins]].<ref name=\"cast & crew\">{{cite news|url=http://www.007.com/bond-returns-in-spectre/ |title=Bond returns in ''Spectre'' |publisher=007.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA2UUvo5 |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=6 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"hvh\">{{cite web|last1=Tapley |first1=Kristopher |title=Interstellar cinematographer on grounding Nolan's movie and shooting Bond on film |url=http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/interstellar-cinematographer-on-grounding-nolans-movie-and-shooting-bond-on-film/single-page |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722044553/http://www.hitfix.com/in-contention/interstellar-cinematographer-on-grounding-nolans-movie-and-shooting-bond-on-film/single-page |archivedate=22 July 2015 |website=[[HitFix]] |accessdate=4 December 2014 |date=20 November 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> In July 2015 Mendes noted that the combined crew of ''Spectre'' numbered over one thousand, making it a larger production than ''Skyfall''.<ref name=\"mendes NSNA\">{{cite web|title=Never Say Never Again (Again) |url=https://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-180715-sam-mendes-interview?t=&s=&id=03930 |date=16 July 2015 |accessdate=17 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722070348/https://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-180715-sam-mendes-interview?t=&s=&id=03930 |archivedate=22 July 2015 |df= }}</ref> Craig is listed as co-producer. He considered the credit a high point of his career, saying, \"I'm just so proud of the fact that my name comes up somewhere else on the titles.\"<ref name=\"after\">{{cite web|title=Daniel Craig may be back as James Bond after Spectre, or not |author=AAP |date=24 October 2015 |url=http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/movies/daniel-craig-may-be-back-as-james-bond-after-spectre-or-not-20151023-gkhh3i |work=Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=3 May 2016 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6q1GCPiit |archivedate=26 April 2017 |url-status=dead |df= |author-link=Australian Associated Press }}</ref>\n\nThe film's usage of the [[SPECTRE|Spectre]] organisation{{refn|name=acronym|group=N|Originally stylised \"SPECTRE\" as an acronym of <u>SP</u>ecial <u>E</u>xecutive for <u>C</u>ounter-intelligence, <u>T</u>errorism, <u>R</u>evenge and <u>E</u>xtortion.}} and its characters marked the end of [[Thunderball (novel)#Writing and copyright|long-standing litigation]] between [[Eon Productions]] and producer [[Kevin McClory]], who sued James Bond creator [[Ian Fleming]] in 1961 claiming ownership over elements of the novel ''[[Thunderball (novel)|Thunderball]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Child |first=Ben |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/nov/18/blofled-spectre-james-bond-kevin-mcclory |title=Blofeld could be back in James Bond's crosshairs following legal deal |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=18 November 2013 |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924202106/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/nov/18/blofled-spectre-james-bond-kevin-mcclory |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df= }}</ref> and in an out of court settlement two years later, was awarded the novel's film rights, including Spectre and its characters.{{refn|name=mcclory|group=N|Following the settlement, McClory collaborated with Eon to produce the adaptation ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' (1965), and  licensed Spectre and its characters to Eon for ten years,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.obsessional.co.uk/castandcrew.htm |title=''Thunderball'' |publisher=Obsessional.co.uk |accessdate=6 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112054502/http://www.obsessional.co.uk/castandcrew.htm |archivedate=12 January 2015 |df= }}</ref> allowing their subsequent appearances in ''[[You Only Live Twice (film)|You Only Live Twice]]'', ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'' and ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]''.}} McClory died in 2006, and in November 2013 MGM and the McClory estate formally settled the issue with [[Danjaq]], LLC\u2014sister company of Eon Productions\u2014with MGM acquiring the full copyright film rights to the concept of Spectre and all of the characters associated with it.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vejvoda |first=Jim |title=MGM, Danjaq Settle James Bond Rights Dispute With McClory Estate |url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2013/11/16/mgm-danjaq-settle-james-bond-rights-dispute-with-mcclory-estate |publisher=IGN |accessdate=5 December 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131120014636/http://ca.ign.com/articles/2013/11/16/mgm-danjaq-settle-james-bond-rights-dispute-with-mcclory-estate |archivedate=20 November 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> It has been suggested that with the acquisition of the film rights and the organisation's re-introduction to the series' continuity, the SPECTRE acronym was discarded and the organisation reimagined as \"Spectre\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Would the world be a better place if James Bond had never existed? |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2015/10/new-film-spectre |accessdate=5 November 2015 |work=[[The Economist]] |date=28 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104171310/https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2015/10/new-film-spectre |archivedate= 4 November 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |title=Synopsis\n |url=http://www.007.com/spectre/\n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6q1GjsMpU\n |archivedate=26 April 2017\n |publisher=[[Eon Productions]]\n |accessdate=5 November 2015\n |url-status=dead\n |df=\n|date=24 August 2015\n }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Here's Why the Next James Bond Film is Called Spectre |url=http://time.com/3618903/spectre-james-bond-movie/ |publisher=[[TIME Magazine]] |accessdate=24 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526173527/http://time.com/3618903/spectre-james-bond-movie/ |archivedate=26 May 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]] renegotiated with [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures]] the deal to co-finance the ''Bond'' franchise in 2011, they were tasked to provide 25 percent of the [[negative cost]] of both ''Skyfall'' and ''Spectre'',  in exchange for receiving 25 percent of the profits plus distribution fees for overseeing its worldwide rollout. When the film was announced in June 2013, the budget was not yet fixed, but was certain to be higher than the $210 million of ''Skyfall'' due to foreign locations and bigger payments for Mendes and Craig.<ref name=thr>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/how-sony-could-lose-james-833474 |title=How Sony Could Lose James Bond After Bloated 'Spectre' (Analysis) |author=Gregg Kilday |work=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131042032/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/how-sony-could-lose-james-833474 |archivedate=31 January 2017 |df= }}</ref> In November 2014, Sony was [[Sony Pictures Entertainment hack|targeted by hackers]] who released details of confidential e-mails between Sony executives regarding several high-profile film projects. Included within these were several memos relating to the production of ''Spectre'', claiming that the film was over budget, detailing early drafts of the script written by [[John Logan (writer)|John Logan]], and expressing Sony's frustration with the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Draft Script for James Bond Film ''Spectre'' Leaked in Sony Hack |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/14/james-bond-spectre-film-script-leaked-sony |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=14 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202015528/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/14/james-bond-spectre-film-script-leaked-sony |archivedate= 2 December 2016 |df= }}</ref> Eon Productions later issued a statement confirming the leak of what they called \"an early version of the screenplay\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement on Spectre |url=http://www.007.com/statement-on-spectre/ |publisher=007.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA34zdDi |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |accessdate=16 December 2014 |date=13 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Eon resisted Sony and MGM's arguments to cut down on stunts and location work to reduce the budget, but managed to secure tax incentives and rebates, such as $14 million from Mexico. ''Spectre'' has a final budget estimated between $250 million and $275 million.<ref name=thr/>\n\n===Writing===\n''Spectre'' marked the return of many scriptwriters from the previous ''Bond'' films, such as ''Skyfall'' writer John Logan;<ref name=\"MendesLogan to return\">{{cite web\n |title=Sam Mendes Returns to Direct\n |url=http://www.007.com/bond-24-news-2/\n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3RpYZ7\n |archivedate= 2 May 2017\n |publisher=[[Eon Productions]]\n |accessdate=4 December 2014\n |date=11 July 2013\n |url-status=dead\n |df=\n}}</ref> [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade]], who had done work in five previous ''Bond'' films;{{refn|name=P&W#5|group=N| [[Neal Purvis and Robert Wade|Purvis and Wade]] were credited for the screenplay of ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'', as they wrote the original draft of the film. However, the final script was written by [[Paul Haggis]], with several uncredited co-writers.<ref name=zetumer>{{cite news|title=A James Bond Set Visit and Seven Exclusive Quantum of Solace Images! |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |date=4 April 2008 |url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/a-james-bond-set-visit-and-seven-exclusive-quantum-of-solace-images/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6q915ftGv |archivedate= 1 May 2017 |accessdate=7 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>}} and British playwright [[Jez Butterworth]], who had previously made uncredited contributions to ''Skyfall''. Butterworth was brought in to polish the script, being helped by Mendes and Craig. Butterworth considered that his changes involved adding what he would like to see as a teenager, and limited the scenes with Bond talking to men, as \"Bond shoots other men\u2014he doesn't sit around chatting to them. So you put a line through that.\"<ref name=jez>{{cite news|last1=Brockes |first1=Emma |title=All or Nothing |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/11/10/nothing-2 |accessdate=16 December 2014 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=10 November 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217004515/http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2014/11/10/nothing-2 |archivedate=17 December 2014 |df= }}</ref> With the acquisition of the rights to Spectre and its associated characters, Purvis and Wade revealed that the film would provide a minor [[retcon]] to the continuity of the previous films, with the Quantum organisation alluded to in ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'' and introduced in ''[[Quantum of Solace]]'' reimagined as a division within Spectre rather than an independent organisation which is implied to be no longer active by the film's events. The plot of ''Spectre'' also linked the events of ''Skyfall'' to Craig's first two ''Bond'' movies by revealing antagonist Raoul Silva to be associated with Spectre reverting ''Skyfall''{{'}}s initial solo story status.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Spectre |journal=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=November 2015 |access-date= }}</ref>\n\nDespite being an original story, ''Spectre'' draws on [[Ian Fleming]]'s [[List of James Bond novels and short stories|source material]], most notably in the character of Franz Oberhauser, played by [[Christoph Waltz]], and his father Hannes. Hannes Oberhauser is a background character in the short story \"[[Octopussy and The Living Daylights#\"Octopussy\"|Octopussy]]\" from the ''[[Octopussy and The Living Daylights]]'' collection, and is named in the film as having been a temporary [[legal guardian]] of a young Bond in 1983.<ref name=\"intertextuality\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/spectre-trailer/ |title=Spectre Trailer&nbsp;\u2013 /Film |work=Slashfilm |df= |date=27 March 2015 }}</ref> As Sam Mendes searched for events in young Bond's life to follow the childhood discussed in ''Skyfall'', he came across Hannes Oberhauser, who becomes a [[father figure]] to Bond. From there, Mendes conceived the idea of \"a natural child who had been [[Cuckoo#Brood parasitism|pushed out, cuckoo in the nest]]\" by Bond, which became Franz.<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |url=http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/18-things-know-spectre/ |title=18 Spectre Secrets Exclusively Revealed By Sam Mendes |first=Emma |last=Thrower |date=9 November 2015 |accessdate=10 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151113034851/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/18-things-know-spectre/ |archivedate=13 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> Similarly, Charmian Bond is shown to have been his full-time guardian, observing the back story established by Fleming.<ref name=\"intertextuality\"/>\n\n===Casting===\n[[File:Monica Bellucci, Women's World Awards 2009 b.jpg|thumb|upright|right|At the age of 50, [[Monica Bellucci]] became the oldest actress to be cast as a [[Bond girl]].]]\n\nThe main cast was revealed in December 2014 at the [[007 Stage]] at [[Pinewood Studios]]. [[Daniel Craig]] returned for his fourth appearance as James Bond, while [[Ralph Fiennes]], [[Naomie Harris]] and [[Ben Whishaw]] reprised their roles as M, Eve Moneypenny and Q respectively, having been established in ''[[Skyfall]]''. [[Rory Kinnear]] also reprised his role as Bill Tanner in his third appearance in the series.<ref name=casting>{{cite news|last=Hawkes |first=Rebecca |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/jamesbond/11271665/Bond-24-title-and-cast-announcement-as-it-happens.html |title=James Bond: Spectre cast announcement: as it happened |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150915113739/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/jamesbond/11271665/Bond-24-title-and-cast-announcement-as-it-happens.html |archivedate=15 September 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nChristoph Waltz was cast in the role of Franz Oberhauser, though he refused to comment on the nature of the part.<ref name=\"huffpost\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/12/04/james-bond-spectre-christoph-waltz-007-villains_n_2003935.html |title=James Bond Villain In 'Spectre' Will Be Christoph Waltz, But Who's 007's Best Villain? (Vote, Pictures) |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qDCBunKh |archivedate= 4 May 2017 |last=Frost |first=Caroline |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=8 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> It was later revealed with the film's release that he is Ernst Stavro Blofeld. Waltz got interested in the film for dealing with technology-assisted [[mass surveillance]], \"speaking about relevant social issues in a way that few ''Bonds'' have done before\", and denied rumours that the role was written specially for him, but added that \"when I came on board, the role grew, evolved, and mutated.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/james-bond-spectre/christoph-waltz-interview/ |date=28 October 2015 |title=Christoph Waltz: 'Facebook is a step toward facism' |work=Daily Telegraph |author=Husband Stuart |accessdate=1 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225093211/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/james-bond-spectre/christoph-waltz-interview/ |archivedate=25 December 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[Dave Bautista]] was cast as Mr. Hinx after producers sought an actor with a background in contact sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.com/us/movies/james-bond/240163/dave-bautista-joining-james-bond-24|title=Bautista Joining James Bond 24|publisher=Den of Geek|date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> The character only has one line in the entire film, \"Shit\". Sam Mendes thought the silent nature would drive Bautista away, but the lifelong Bond fan expressed interest in reviving the quiet henchman archetype of characters such as [[Jaws (James Bond)|Jaws]]. Bautista's performance was inspired mostly by [[Oddjob]] from ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/11/03/dave-bautista-spectre-villain-a-cross-between-jaws-and-oddjob |title=Spectre: Dave Bautista laughed off James Bond nose injury|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=28 February 2017}}</ref> and said not talking created an acting challenge, \"trying to find this way where I am actually going to have speak without speaking.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://home.bt.com/news/showbiz-news/spectre-dave-bautista-laughed-off-james-bond-nose-injury-11364014084292 |title=Spectre: Dave Bautista laughed off James Bond nose injury |publisher=[[BT Consumer|BT.com]] |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=28 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105193756/http://home.bt.com/news/showbiz-news/spectre-dave-bautista-laughed-off-james-bond-nose-injury-11364014084292 |archivedate= 5 January 2016 |df= }}</ref> After casting [[B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Marlohe|B\u00e9r\u00e9nice Lim Marlohe]], a relative newcomer, as S\u00e9v\u00e9rine in ''Skyfall'', Mendes sought out a more experienced actor for the role of Madeleine Swann, ultimately casting [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]] in the role.<ref>{{cite news|last=Barraclough |first=Leo |url=https://variety.com/2014/film/global/bond-24-titled-new-cast-members-revealed-1201370782/ |title=Bond 24 Titled 'Spectre', New Cast Members Revealed |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002000613/http://variety.com/2014/film/global/bond-24-titled-new-cast-members-revealed-1201370782/ |archivedate= 2 October 2015 |df= }}</ref> [[Monica Bellucci]] joined the cast as Lucia Sciarra, becoming, at the age of fifty, the oldest actress to be cast as a [[Bond girl]]. In a separate interview with Danish website Euroman, [[Jesper Christensen]] revealed he would be reprising his role as Mr. White from ''[[Casino Royale (2006 film)|Casino Royale]]'' and ''[[Quantum of Solace]]''.<ref name=\"Euroman.dk\"/><ref name=\"Empire-Christensen\"/> Christensen's character was reportedly killed off in a scene intended to be used as an epilogue to ''Quantum of Solace'', before it was removed from the final cut of the film, enabling his return in ''Spectre''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/qos-mr-white-cut-scene?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03844 |title=The Fate Of Mr. White |work=MI6-HQ.COM |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402105625/http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/qos-mr-white-cut-scene?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03844 |archivedate= 2 April 2015 |df= |date=8 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the principal cast, Alessandro Cremona was cast as Marco Sciarra, [[Stephanie Sigman]] was cast as Estrella, and [[Detlef Bothe (actor)|Detlef Bothe]] was cast as a villain for scenes shot in Austria.<ref name=\"cremona\">{{cite news|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/features/424009-cs-visits-james-bond-in-mexico-city-and-learns-how-spectre-begins#/slide/1 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qEs6b0zr |archivedate= 5 May 2017 |title=CS visits James Bond in Mexico City and learns how ''Spectre'' begins |publisher=comingsoon.net |accessdate=1 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"sigman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.007.com/stephanie-sigman-joins-spectre/ |title=Stephanie Sigman Joins ''Spectre'' |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3WnwBn |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |publisher=007.com |date=9 March 2015 |accessdate=10 March 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-010315-detlef-bothe-interview?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03859 |title=Detlef Bothe Speaks |work=MI6-HQ.COM |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029173448/https://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-010315-detlef-bothe-interview?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03859 |archivedate=29 October 2015 |df= |date=March 2015 }}</ref> In February 2015 over fifteen hundred extras were hired for the pre-title sequence set in Mexico, though they were duplicated in the film, giving the effect of around ten thousand extras.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cant\u00fa |first1=Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 |title=Buscan espectros mexicanos para James Bond |url=http://www.milenio.com/hey/cine/Buscan-espectros-mexicanos-James-Bond_0_460153998.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qEpTwrox |archivedate= 5 May 2017 |accessdate=16 February 2015 |agency=Milenio |publisher=Milenio |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Filmar\u00e1 007 9 d\u00edas en el DF|url=http://www.larazonsanluis.com/index.php/agencia-reforma/espectaculos/item/65595-filmara-007-9-dias-en-el-df|accessdate=16 February 2015|agency=Reform Agency|publisher=Reform Agency|date=16 February 2015 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150423220714/http://larazonsanluis.com/index.php/agencia-reforma/espectaculos/item/65595-filmara-007-9-dias-en-el-df | archive-date =23 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=emp0415/><ref name=\"delve deep\">{{cite web|last1=Nicholson |first1=Max |last2=Cornet |first2=Roth |title=James Bond Producers Delve Deep Into Spectre |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/29/james-bond-producers-delve-deep-into-spectre |website=IGN |accessdate=29 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401040600/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/03/29/james-bond-producers-delve-deep-into-spectre |archivedate= 1 April 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nMendes revealed that production would begin on 8 December 2014 at Pinewood Studios, with filming taking seven months.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller |first1=Ross |title=The next James Bond film is called Spectre: new car, poster, and full cast confirmed |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/12/4/7327013/james-bond-24-full-cast-title-car-release-date |website=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=4 December 2014 |date=4 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209092435/http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/4/7327013/james-bond-24-full-cast-title-car-release-date |archivedate= 9 December 2014 |df= }}</ref> Mendes also confirmed several filming locations, including [[London]], [[Mexico City]] and [[Rome]]. Van Hoytema shot the film mostly on [[Kodak]] [[35mm movie film|35&nbsp;mm film]] stock (in addition to digital cameras such as the [[Arri Alexa#Alexa 65|6K Arri Alexa 65mm]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nofilmschool.com/2015/11/director-sam-mendes-35mm-film-james-bond-spectre|title=Director Sam Mendes on Going Back to 35mm for 'Spectre'|date=2015-11-01|website=No Film School|language=en|access-date=2019-08-13}}</ref>), in contrast to ''Skyfall'' being filmed solely on digital cameras.<ref>{{cite web|title=Film Capture Powers the Visually Stunning SPECTRE|date=4 November 2015|url=http://www.kodak.com/US/en/motion/Blog/Blog_Post/?contentId=4294991985|publisher=Kodak|accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref> Early filming took place at Pinewood Studios, and around [[London]], with scenes variously featuring Craig and Harris at Bond's flat, and Craig and Kinnear travelling down the [[River Thames]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond23-gallery-london-filming-december15?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03809 |title=London Filming (1) |work=MI6-HQ.COM |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402195239/http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond23-gallery-london-filming-december15?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03809 |archivedate= 2 April 2015 |df= |date=15 December 2014 }}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align     = left\n| direction = vertical\n| header   =\n| width     = 200\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = JAGUAR C-X75 HYBRID SUPERCAR (9098871512).jpg\n| width1    =\n| alt1      =\n| caption1  = After being cancelled in 2012, the [[Jaguar C-X75]] was recommissioned to appear in ''Spectre''.\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Aston Martin DB10 2015.jpg\n| width2    =\n| alt2      =\n| caption2  = The [[Aston Martin DB10]] is driven by Bond in the film.\n<!-- Image 3 -->\n| image3    = Aston Martin DB5 (Skyfall).jpg\n| width3    =\n| alt3      =\n| caption3  = The [[Aston Martin DB5]] reappears after reconstruction in Q's workshop at the film's ending, with Bond driving away with it.\n}}\nFilming was carried out in Austria between December 2014 and February 2015, with production taking place in the area around [[S\u00f6lden]]\u2014including the [[\u00d6tztal Glacier Road]], [[Rettenbach glacier]] and the adjacent ski resort plus cable car station\u2014[[Obertilliach]] and [[Altaussee|Lake Altaussee]].<ref>{{cite tweet |user=007 |number=540461455955742720 |title=#SPECTRE will be filming at Pinewood London, Mexico City, Rome, Tangier & Erfoud, Morocco, S\u00f6lden, Obertilliach and Lake Altausee, Austria |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=4 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128114506/https://twitter.com/007/status/540461455955742720 |archivedate=28 January 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"vipers\">{{cite news|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/james-bond-new-007-film-details-to-be-announced-live-from-pinewood-studios-9902204.html |title=James Bond: new 007 film to be called 'Spectre' with Christoph Waltz confirmed as villain |last=Vipers |first=Gareth |work=[[London Evening Standard]] |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=4 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204145516/http://www.standard.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/james-bond-new-007-film-details-to-be-announced-live-from-pinewood-studios-9902204.html |archivedate= 4 December 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=S\u00f6lden&nbsp;\u2013 filming location for the new James Bond Movie |url=http://www.soelden.com/james-bond-007-en |first1=Jakob |last1=Falkner |first2=Oliver |last2=Swartz |publisher=soelden.com |date=5 December 2014 |accessdate=7 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208180346/http://www.soelden.com/james-bond-007-en |archivedate=8 December 2014 |df= }}</ref> Scenes filmed in Austria centred on the Ice Q Restaurant, standing in for the fictional Hoffler Klinik, a private medical clinic in the [[Austrian Alps]]. Filming included an action scene featuring a [[Land Rover Defender|Land Rover Defender Bigfoot]] and a [[Range Rover Sport]].<ref name=\"cx75\">{{cite web|title=Jaguar and Land Rover Announce Partnership with Spectre the 24th James Bond Adventure |url=http://www.jaguar.com/news/jlr-james-bond-partnership.html |accessdate=13 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150213075744/http://www.jaguar.com/news/jlr-james-bond-partnership.html |archivedate=13 February 2015 |df= }}</ref> Various airplane models were used in filming, from a life-sized plane with detachable wings to film the crash in the woods, to plane fuselages either built atop [[snowmobile]]s or shot from nitrogen cannons.<ref name=fxguide/> Production was temporarily halted first by an injury to Craig, who sprained his knee whilst shooting a fight scene,<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Daniel Craig Returns To ''Spectre'' Today After Knee Injury Earlier This Week |url=http://deadline.com/2015/02/daniel-craig-returns-to-spectre-today-after-knee-injury-earlier-this-week-1201368678/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210071916/http://deadline.com/2015/02/daniel-craig-returns-to-spectre-today-after-knee-injury-earlier-this-week-1201368678/ |archivedate=10 February 2015 |df= |date=7 February 2015 }}</ref> and later by an accident involving a filming vehicle that saw three crew members injured, at least one of them seriously.<ref>{{cite web|title=3 Injured during filming of new Bond flick in Austria|url= http://www.efe.com/efe/english/varios/injured-during-filming-new-bond-flick-austria/50000269-2542386 |publisher=efe.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Agence France Press |title=Two technicians seriously injured on James Bond set in Austria |url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/entertainment/2015/02/18/Two-technicians-seriously-injured-on-James-Bond-set-in-Austria-.html |publisher=Al Arabiya |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306224201/http://english.alarabiya.net/en/life-style/entertainment/2015/02/18/Two-technicians-seriously-injured-on-James-Bond-set-in-Austria-.html |archivedate= 6 March 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFilming temporarily returned to England to shoot scenes at [[Blenheim Palace]] in [[Oxfordshire]], which stood in for a location in Rome, before moving on to the city itself for a five-week shoot across the city, with locations including the [[Ponte Sisto]] bridge and the [[Roman Forum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.007.com/spectre-moves-to-rome/ |title=''Spectre'' moves to Rome |publisher=007.com |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3alBpa |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |accessdate=2 March 2015 |date=19 February 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The production faced opposition from a variety of special interest groups and city authorities, who were concerned about the potential for damage to historical sites around the city, and problems with graffiti and rubbish appearing in the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-20150219-rome-filming-day1?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03852 |title=Rome Filming |work=MI6-HQ.COM |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402184911/http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-20150219-rome-filming-day1?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03852 |archivedate= 2 April 2015 |df= |date=19 February 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-20150109-rome-car-chase-quattro-fontane?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03828 |title=Arrivederci Mr. Bond |work=MI6-HQ.COM |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402220846/http://www.mi6-hq.com/sections/articles/bond-24-report-20150109-rome-car-chase-quattro-fontane?t=&s=mi6_update&id=03828 |archivedate= 2 April 2015 |df= |date=9 January 2015 }}</ref> Special effects supervisor [[Chris Corbould]] stated the scenes had to be extensively planned prior to filming specially to avoid any mishaps, going to the point of building protection above steps where cars would drive.<ref name=fxguide/> A car chase scene set along the banks of the [[Tiber River]] and through the streets of Rome<ref>{{cite web|title=8 Spectre locations to see in Rome|url=http://www.movietrip.me/trips/view/33/travel-like-james-bond---8-'spectre'-locations-to-see-in-rome|website=Movietrip.me|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref> featured an [[Aston Martin DB10]] (a model developed especially for the film, with only 10 examples produced<ref>{{cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=21 January 2016 |title=Unique Opportunity to Own an Aston Martin DB10 Predicted to Raise Over \u00a31 Million for Charity |url=http://www2.astonmartin.com/live/news/2016/01/21/unique-opportunity-to-own-an-aston-martin-db10-predicted-to-raise-over-1-million-for-charity |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411111443/http://www2.astonmartin.com/live/news/2016/01/21/unique-opportunity-to-own-an-aston-martin-db10-predicted-to-raise-over-1-million-for-charity |archive-date=11 April 2016 |website=Aston Martin |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref>) and a [[Jaguar C-X75]].<ref name=\"cx75\"/> The C-X75 was originally developed as a [[hybrid electric vehicle]] with four independent electric engines powered by two jet turbines, before the project was cancelled.<ref name=MT092810>{{cite news|url=http://www.motortrend.com/news/jaguar-c-x75-concept/ |title=First Look: Jaguar C-X75 Concept |work=[[Motor Trend]] |date=28 September 2010 |accessdate=28 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112031123/http://www.motortrend.com/news/jaguar-c-x75-concept/ |archivedate=12 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> The version used for filming was converted to use a conventional [[internal combustion engine]], to minimise the potential for disruption from mechanical problems with the complex hybrid system. The C-X75s used for filming were developed by the engineering division of Formula One racing team [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]], who built the original C-X75 prototype for Jaguar.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://jalopnik.com/everything-you-havent-seen-yet-about-spectres-jaguar-c-1730568764?rev=1442255691259 |title=Everything you haven't seen yet about ''Spectre''{{'}}s Jaguar C-X75 |work=jalopnik |accessdate=15 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001134746/http://jalopnik.com/everything-you-havent-seen-yet-about-spectres-jaguar-c-1730568764?rev=1442255691259 |archivedate= 1 October 2015 |df= }}</ref> Remote driving pods were built above the cars so the vehicles could be driven while the cameras focused on Craig and Bautista in the steering wheel.<ref name=fxguide/> According to chief stunt co-ordinator Gary Powell, filming the chase had the \"risk of skidding into the [[Vatican City|Vatican]]\", and led to \"a record for smashing up cars in ''Spectre''\u2014seven Aston Martins in all,\" with the film's car expenses estimated at \u00a324 million ($48 million).<ref>{{cite news|last=Chittley |first=Jordan |title=New Bond movie destroys $48-million worth of sweet rides |date=2 October 2015 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-drive/news/trans-canada-highway/new-bond-movie-destroys-48-million-worth-of-sweet-rides/article26633902/ |accessdate=15 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927231350/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/globe-drive/news/trans-canada-highway/new-bond-movie-destroys-48-million-worth-of-sweet-rides/article26633902/ |archivedate=27 September 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nWith filming completed in Rome, production moved to [[Mexico City]] in late March to shoot the film's opening sequence, with scenes to include the [[Day of the Dead]] festival filmed in and around the [[Z\u00f3calo]] and the [[Historic center of Mexico City|Centro Hist\u00f3rico]] district.<ref>{{cite web|title=James Bond se apodera del Centro Hist\u00f3rico |url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/funcion/2015/03/17/1013869#imagen-2 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150320010859/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/funcion/2015/03/17/1013869 |archivedate=20 March 2015 |url-status=live |website=Excelsion Newspaper Online |accessdate=19 March 2015 |df= |date=17 March 2015 }}</ref> At the time, no such Day of the Dead parade like the one from the film took place in Mexico City; in 2016, due to the interest raised by ''Spectre'' and the government's desire to promote the [[Pre-Columbian era|pre-Hispanic]] Mexican culture, the federal and local authorities decided to organize an actual \"D\u00eda de Muertos\" parade through [[Paseo de la Reforma]] and [[Historic center of Mexico City|Centro Hist\u00f3rico]] on 29 October 2016, which was attended by 250,000 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-37813562 |title=Mexico City stages first Day of the Dead parade |work=[[BBC]] |date=29 October 2016 |accessdate=1 November 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030142729/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-37813562 |archivedate=30 October 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/comunidad/2016/10/30/1125178#imagen-3 |title=Fotogaler\u00eda: Desfile por D\u00eda de Muertos re\u00fane a 250 mil personas |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161031150523/http://www.excelsior.com.mx/comunidad/2016/10/30/1125178%23 |archivedate=31 October 2016 |url-status=live |work=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]] |date=29 October 2016 |accessdate=1 November 2016 |language=spanish |df= }}</ref>  The film opens with a [[long take]] that joins six shots seamlessly, and was one of the few scenes that required [[previsualization]]. Through extensive planning, filming did not require [[motion control]] cameras. The [[Split edit|scene joints]] were done in post-production through re-timing and re-[[Rear projection effect|projections]], which even matched Mexico locations with interiors filmed at Pinewood.<ref name=fxguide>{{cite web|url=https://www.fxguide.com/featured/spectre-acular-special-effects/ |title=Spectre-acular effects |publisher=FXguide |first=Ian |last=Failes |date=16 November 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225105858/https://www.fxguide.com/featured/spectre-acular-special-effects/ |archivedate=25 February 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Calle de la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico cerrado por la grabaci\u00f3n de Spectre.jpg|thumb|right|Filming of the Mexico City scenes, revolving around a [[Day of the Dead]] parade.]]\nThe planned scenes required the city square to be closed for filming a sequence involving a fight aboard a [[MBB Bo 105|Messerschmitt-B\u00f6lkow-Blohm Bo 105]] helicopter flown by stunt pilot [[Chuck Aaron]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/spectre-opening-sequence-description/ |title=Spectre Opening Sequence Description: Find Out How Bond 24 Begins |work=Collider |author=Weintraub, Steve |date=27 March 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324121023/http://collider.com/spectre-opening-sequence-description/ |archivedate=24 March 2016 |df= }}</ref> which called for modifications to be made to several buildings to prevent damage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Inician Ensayos de escenas de Spectre en El Zocalo |url=http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/2015/inician-ensayos-de-escenas-de-39spectre-39-en-el-zocalo-1085857.html |website=Periodico El Universal |accessdate=19 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804093150/http://archivo.eluniversal.com.mx/espectaculos/2015/inician-ensayos-de-escenas-de-39spectre-39-en-el-zocalo-1085857.html |archivedate= 4 August 2015 |df= }}</ref> This particular scene in Mexico required 1,500 extras, 10 giant skeletons and 250,000 paper flowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imagining-james-bonds-bachelor-pad-833158 |title=Imagining James Bond's Bachelor Pad |author=Cathy Whitlock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=22 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021205106/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imagining-james-bonds-bachelor-pad-833158 |archivedate=21 October 2015 |df= }}</ref> Reports in the Mexican media added that the film's second unit would move to [[Palenque, Chiapas|Palenque]] in the state of [[Chiapas]], to film aerial manoeuvres considered too dangerous to shoot in an urban area.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://expansion.mx/entretenimiento/2015/04/08/palenque-la-ultima-escala-de-james-bond-en-su-aventura-mexicana|title=Palenque, la \u00faltima escala de James Bond en su aventura mexicana|work=[[Expansi\u00f3n (Mexico)|Expansi\u00f3n]]|date=8 April 2015|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref> These were pasted over a computer-generated square and crowd below the helicopter, with [[motion capture]] doubles fighting inside. Mendes and the effects team felt that this approach \"would get believable composition and movement\" compared to adding a digital helicopter above the Mexico City location.<ref name=begg>{{cite web|title=Spectre: Steve Begg \u2013 Production VFX Supervisor |first=Vincent |last=Frei |url=http://www.artofvfx.com/spectre-steve-begg-production-vfx-supervisor/ |accessdate=6 April 2017 |publisher=Art of VFX |date=16 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021034356/http://www.artofvfx.com/spectre-steve-begg-production-vfx-supervisor/ |archivedate=21 October 2016 |df= }}</ref> Following filming in Mexico, and during a scheduled break, Craig was flown to New York to undergo minor surgery to fix his knee injury. It was reported that filming was not affected and he had returned to filming at Pinewood Studios as planned on 22 April.<ref>{{cite news|title=Daniel Craig has knee surgery after Bond injury |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32189448 |accessdate=6 April 2015 |publisher=BBC News |date=5 April 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150406015333/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32189448 |archivedate= 6 April 2015 |df= }}</ref> Nonetheless, some parts of the Mexico scene were done with stunt doubles, whose faces were digitally replaced with Craig's.<ref name=fxguide/>\n\nOn 17 May 2015 filming took place on the Thames in London. Stunt scenes involving Craig and Seydoux on a speedboat as well as a low flying helicopter near [[Westminster Bridge]] were shot at night, with filming temporarily closing both Westminster and [[Lambeth Bridge]]s. Scenes were also shot on the river near [[SIS Building|MI6's headquarters]] at Vauxhall Cross.<ref name=BBCMay15>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-32777018 |title=James Bond fans see filming of Spectre on River Thames in London |date=18 May 2015 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=20 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521005934/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-32777018 |archivedate=21 May 2015 |df= }}</ref> The crew returned to the river less than a week later to film scenes solely set on Westminster Bridge. The [[London Fire Brigade]] was on set to simulate rain as well as monitor smoke used for filming. Craig, Seydoux, and Waltz, as well as Harris and Fiennes, were seen being filmed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spectre attacks Big Ben as James Bond returns to do battle with old enemy |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/spectre-attacks-big-ben-james-5752224 |accessdate=24 May 2015 |work=Mirror |date=24 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150525000355/http://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/spectre-attacks-big-ben-james-5752224 |archivedate=25 May 2015 |df= }}</ref> Prior to this, scenes involving Fiennes were shot at a restaurant in [[Covent Garden]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Spectre filming at Rules restaurant in London |url=http://www.jamesbondlifestyle.com/news/spectre-filming-rules-restaurant-london |accessdate=24 May 2015 |work=James Bond Lifestyle |date=23 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524214342/http://www.jamesbondlifestyle.com/news/spectre-filming-rules-restaurant-london |archivedate=24 May 2015 |df= }}</ref> Blofeld's helicopter crash was done with two full sized helicopter shells, which were rigged with steelwork and an overhead track. Computer-generated rotor blades and scenery damage were added in post-production. The [[SIS Building|MI6 building]], which in the film is vacated and scheduled for demolition following the terrorist attack from ''Skyfall'', was replaced in the production plates for a digital reconstruction. When the building is detonated, it is a combination of both a miniature and a breakaway version of the digital building.<ref name=fxguide/>\n\nAfter wrapping up in England, production travelled to Morocco in June, with filming taking place in [[Oujda]], [[Tangier]] and [[Erfoud]], after preliminary work was completed by the production's second unit.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/artisans/news/spectre-king-tut-and-the-book-of-the-dead-sail-to-morocco-1201372107/ |title='Spectre', 'King Tut' and 'The Book of the Dead' Sail To Morocco |date=6 December 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2015 |work=Variety |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315173521/http://variety.com/2014/artisans/news/spectre-king-tut-and-the-book-of-the-dead-sail-to-morocco-1201372107/ |archivedate=15 March 2015 |df= }}</ref> The headquarters of Spectre in Morocco was located in [[Gara Medouar]] which is a 'crater' caused by erosion and of neither volcanic nor impact origin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebondbulletin.com/gara-medouar-the-spectre-villain-lair |title=Gara Medouar \u2013 The Spectre volcano lair that isn't a volcano |first=Benjamin |last=Lind |publisher=The Bond Bulletin |date=29 November 2015 |accessdate=1 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161102135517/http://www.thebondbulletin.com/gara-medouar-the-spectre-villain-lair |archivedate= 2 November 2016 |df= }}</ref> An explosion filmed in Morocco holds a [[Guinness World Record]] for the \"Largest film stunt explosion\" in cinematic history, involving 8,140 litres of kerosene and 24 charges each with a kilogram of high explosives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2015/11/daniel-craig-accepts-certificate-for-largest-film-stunt-explosion-in-latest-bond-405307 |title=Latest Bond adventure Spectre sets record for Largest film stunt explosion ever&nbsp;\u2013 watch incredible clip |author=Rachel Swatman |work=[[Guinness World Records]] |date=10 November 2015 |accessdate=11 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151111203646/http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2015/11/daniel-craig-accepts-certificate-for-largest-film-stunt-explosion-in-latest-bond-405307 |archivedate=11 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> [[Principal photography]] concluded on 5 July 2015. A wrap-up party for ''Spectre'' was held in commemoration before entering post-production.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=11789&t=mi6&s=news |title=It's a wrap for 'SPECTRE' as principal photography ends |accessdate=5 July 2015 |publisher=Mi6-HQ.com |date=5 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707044040/https://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=11789&t=mi6&s=news |archivedate= 7 July 2015 |df= }}</ref> Filming took 128 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.clicknews.co/2015/07/05/james-bond-007-spectre-assassin-marco-sciarra-says-goodbye-clapperboard-collection/ |title=James Bond 007 Spectre&nbsp;\u2013 Assassin \"Marco Sciarra\" Says Goodbye / Clapperboard Collection |accessdate=6 July 2015 |work=Clicknews |date=5 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712155526/http://www.clicknews.co/2015/07/05/james-bond-007-spectre-assassin-marco-sciarra-says-goodbye-clapperboard-collection/ |archivedate=12 July 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nWhilst filming in Mexico City, speculation in the media claimed that the script had been altered to accommodate the demands of Mexican authorities\u2014reportedly influencing details of the scene and characters, casting choices, and modifying the script to portray the country in a \"positive light\"\u2014to secure tax concessions and financial support worth up to $20 million for the film.<ref name=\"h'wood report\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spectre-james-bond-film-reportedly-781497 |title='Spectre': James Bond Film Reportedly Receiving $20M for Portraying Mexico Positively |author=John Hecht |work=The Hollywood Reporter |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316204401/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spectre-james-bond-film-reportedly-781497 |archivedate=16 March 2015 |df= }}</ref> This was denied by producer Michael G. Wilson,<ref name=\"h'wood report\"/> who stated that the scene had always been intended to be shot in Mexico as production had been attracted to the imagery of the Day of the Dead, and that the script had been developed from there.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/19/james-bond-producer-says-mexico-didnt-spectre-change-in-the-script |title=James Bond producer says Mexico didn't make changes to ''Spectre'' script |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=19 March 2015 |accessdate=20 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319083841/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/mar/19/james-bond-producer-says-mexico-didnt-spectre-change-in-the-script |archivedate=19 March 2015 |df= }}</ref> Production of ''[[Skyfall]]'' had previously faced similar problems while attempting to secure permits to shoot the film's pre-title sequence in India before moving to Istanbul.<ref name=\"Inde\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/James-Bonds-author-was-friend-of-Gujarat-royalty/articleshow/17250680.cms |title=James Bond's author was friend of Gujarat royalty |work=[[The Times of India]] |location=Mumbai |date=17 November 2012 |accessdate=20 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922235258/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/James-Bonds-author-was-friend-of-Gujarat-royalty/articleshow/17250680.cms |archivedate=22 September 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFive companies did the [[visual effects]]\u2014[[Industrial Light & Magic]], [[Double Negative (VFX)|Double Negative]], [[Moving Picture Company]], [[Cinesite]] and Peerless\u2014under the supervision of Steve Begg. The computer-generated effects included [[Matte (filmmaking)|set extensions]], digital touches on the vehicles, and crumbling buildings.<ref name=fxguide/><ref name=begg/> A sixth one, [[Framestore]], handled the [[Motifs in the James Bond film series#Title sequence|title sequence]], the seventh in the series designed by [[Daniel Kleinman]]. It took four months to complete, and centred on an [[octopus]] motif reminiscent of the Spectre logo, along with images of love and relationships.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/spectre-titles-design-framestore/ |title=Spectre titles design: How Framestore combined explosions and octopi for James Bond's latest film |work=Digital Arts Online |first=Michael |last=Burns |date=18 November 2015 |accessdate=20 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930000423/http://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/motion-graphics/spectre-titles-design-framestore/ |archivedate=30 September 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{main|Spectre: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack}}\n[[Thomas Newman]] returned as ''Spectre''{{'}}s composer.<ref name=\"cast & crew\"/> Rather than composing the score once the film had moved into post-production, Newman worked during filming.<ref name=\"delve deep\"/> The theatrical trailer released in July 2015 contained a rendition of [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]'s ''[[On Her Majesty's Secret Service (film)|On Her Majesty's Secret Service]]'' theme.<ref name=\"OHMSS sample\">{{cite web|title=New Spectre Trailer |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LTDaET-JweU |website=You Tube |accessdate=30 July 2015 |date=21 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150729180830/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LTDaET-JweU |archivedate=29 July 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Trailer soundtrack\">{{cite web|last1=Ross |first1=Daniel |title=New Bond soundtrack: what does the new Spectre trailer tell us? |url=http://www.classicfm.com/composers/newman/news/james-bond-spectre-soundtrack/#QEke7FmlEbKd4XIp.97 |website=Classic FM |accessdate=30 July 2015 |date=22 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801234554/http://www.classicfm.com/composers/newman/news/james-bond-spectre-soundtrack/ |archivedate= 1 August 2015 |df= }}</ref> Mendes stated that the final film would have more than one hundred minutes of music.<ref name=\"mendes NSNA\"/> The soundtrack album was released on 23 October 2015 in the UK and 6 November 2015 in the US on [[Decca Records]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas Newman&nbsp;\u2013 James Bond: Spectre (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack) |url=http://www.love-melody.com/2015/10/james-bond-spectre-soundtrack.html |publisher=Love Melodey |date=23 October 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118100039/http://www.love-melody.com/2015/10/james-bond-spectre-soundtrack.html |archivedate=18 November 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas Newman&nbsp;\u2013 Spectre (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)|url=http://www.discogs.com/Thomas-Newman-Spectre-Original-Motion-Picture-Soundtrack/release/7636807|publisher=[[discogs]]|date=23 October 2015|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe English band [[Radiohead]] were commissioned to write the title song, and submitted \"[[Man of War (song)|Man of War]]\", an unreleased song written in the 1990s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/06/radiohead-share-video-for-previously-unreleased-song-man-of-war-watch/|title=Radiohead share video for previously unreleased song \"Man of War\" |last=|first=|date=22 June 2017|work=Consequence of Sound|access-date=29 July 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The song was rejected as it had not been written for the film and therefore was ineligible for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b09clppp|title=Sam Mendes, Sound and Vision |last=|first=|date=5 November 2017|website=BBC Radio 6 Music|access-date=6 November 2017}}</ref> Radiohead recorded another song for the film, \"[[Spectre (song)|Spectre]]\", but this was also rejected as too melancholy.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/19-things-we-learned-hanging-out-with-radiohead-w486278|title=19 Things We Learned Hanging Out With Radiohead|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=8 June 2017|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=8 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" />\n\nIn September 2015, Eon announced that [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]] had recorded the title theme, \"[[Writing's on the Wall (Sam Smith song)|Writing's on the Wall]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.007.com/sam-smith-to-sing-title-song-for-spectre/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3g9pl5 |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |title=Sam Smith to Sing Title Song for Spectre |publisher=[[Eon Productions]] |date=8 September 2015 |accessdate=8 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Smith said the song came together in one session and that he and regular collaborator [[Jimmy Napes]] wrote it in under half an hour before recording a [[demo (music)|demo]]. Satisfied with the quality, the filmmakers used the demo in the final release.<ref name=\"NPR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/09/25/442558641/hear-sam-smith-break-down-his-bond-theme-writings-on-the-wall |title=Hear Sam Smith Break Down His Bond Theme, 'Writing's On The Wall' |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=25 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925203129/http://www.npr.org/2015/09/25/442558641/hear-sam-smith-break-down-his-bond-theme-writings-on-the-wall |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df= }}</ref> \"Writing's on the Wall\" was released as a download on 25 September 2015.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sam Smith's 'Writing's on the Wall' is the Theme of New Bond Film Spectre |url=http://time.com/4024712/sam-smith-james-bond-theme-spectre-writings-on-the-wall/ |work=Time |accessdate=8 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150908235857/http://time.com/4024712/sam-smith-james-bond-theme-spectre-writings-on-the-wall/ |archivedate= 8 September 2015 |df= }}</ref> It received mixed reviews from critics and fans, particularly in comparison to [[Adele]]'s \"[[Skyfall (Adele song)|Skyfall]]\",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/sep/25/sam-smith-james-bond-theme-writing-on-the-wall |title=Sam Smith's James Bond theme review&nbsp;\u2013 'It feels like an X Factor ballad' |first=Alexis |last=Petridis |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=25 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925211354/http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/sep/25/sam-smith-james-bond-theme-writing-on-the-wall |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/09/25/sam-smith-writings-on-the-wall-james-bond-song-spectre_n_8194356.html |title=Sam Smith's ''Writing On The Wall'' ''Spectre'' Song Hasn't Impressed ''James Bond'' Fans |first=Rachel |last=McGrath |work=[[The Huffington Post|The Huffington Post UK]] |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=25 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925220230/http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2015/09/25/sam-smith-writings-on-the-wall-james-bond-song-spectre_n_8194356.html |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34357110 |title=Sam Smith Bond song splits opinion |publisher=BBC News |date=25 September 2015 |accessdate=25 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925210138/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-34357110 |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crushable.com/2015/09/25/entertainment/sam-smith-bond-theme-twitter-response-bad/ |title=Twitter Reacts Badly To Sam Smith's New Bond Theme |work=Crushable |accessdate=1 April 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305131930/http://www.crushable.com/2015/09/25/entertainment/sam-smith-bond-theme-twitter-response-bad/ |archivedate= 5 March 2016 |df= }}</ref> leading to [[Shirley Bassey]] trending on [[Twitter]] on the day it was released.<ref name=\"Inde\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/sam-smiths-james-bond-theme-song-writings-on-the-wall-makes-shirley-bassey-trend-on-twitter-because-10516519.html |title=Sam Smith's James Bond theme song 'Writing's On The Wall' makes Shirley Bassey trend on Twitter because people hate it |work=The Independent |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114011956/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/sam-smiths-james-bond-theme-song-writings-on-the-wall-makes-shirley-bassey-trend-on-twitter-because-10516519.html |archivedate=14 November 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/sam-smith/news/sam-smith-releases-new-bond-theme-but-twitter-reckons-hes-no-shirley-bassey |title=Sam Smith Releases New Bond Theme But Twitter Reckons He's No Shirley Bassey |work=MTV UK |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925212238/http://www.mtv.co.uk/sam-smith/news/sam-smith-releases-new-bond-theme-but-twitter-reckons-hes-no-shirley-bassey |archivedate=25 September 2015 |df= }}</ref> Despite the mixed reception, it became the first Bond theme to reach number one in the [[UK Singles Chart]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/oct/02/sam-smith-writings-on-the-wall-first-ever-bond-no-1-disclosure-caracal |title=Sam Smith's \"Writing's on the Wall\" becomes first ever Bond No. 1 |first=Hannah |last=Ellis-Petersen |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 October 2015 |accessdate=16 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016124415/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/oct/02/sam-smith-writings-on-the-wall-first-ever-bond-no-1-disclosure-caracal |archivedate=16 October 2015 |df= }}</ref> the second to win the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]],<ref name=\"SamSmithSongOscar2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/feb/29/sam-smith-wins-the-best-song-oscar-for-his-james-bond-spectre-theme |title=Sam Smith wins the best song Oscar for his James Bond Spectre theme |first=Henry |last=Barnes |date=29 February 2016 |accessdate=28 May 2016 |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419120354/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/feb/29/sam-smith-wins-the-best-song-oscar-for-his-james-bond-spectre-theme |archivedate=19 April 2016 |df= }}</ref> and the fifth to be nominated.<ref name=\"SamSmithSongOscar\">{{cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2016/02/spectre-sam-smith-jimmy-napes-wins-oscar-best-original-song-2016-academy-award-winner-1201710612/ |title=Sam Smith & Jimmy Napes Win Oscar For 'Spectre' Original Song 'Writing's On The Wall' |first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |date=28 February 2016 |accessdate=28 May 2016 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160528160650/http://deadline.com/2016/02/spectre-sam-smith-jimmy-napes-wins-oscar-best-original-song-2016-academy-award-winner-1201710612/ |archivedate=28 May 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/28/entertainment/oscars-2016-winners-list-feat/index.html |title=The 2016 Oscars winners list |first=Katia |last=Hetter |date=28 February 2016 |accessdate=28 February 2016 |publisher=[[CNN]] ([[Time Warner]]) |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160229020329/http://www.cnn.com/2016/02/28/entertainment/oscars-2016-winners-list-feat/index.html |archivedate=29 February 2016 |df= }}</ref>{{refn|The other four were \"[[Skyfall (Adele song)|Skyfall]]\" (2012), \"\"[[For Your Eyes Only (song)|For Your Eyes Only]]\" (1981), \"[[Nobody Does It Better]]\" (1977), and \"[[Live and Let Die (song)|Live and Let Die]]\" (1973).<ref name=\"SamSmithSongOscar\"/><ref name=\"SamSmithSongOscar2\"/>|name=Bond Theme Song Record|group=N}} It also won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] at the [[73rd Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merry|first1=Stephanie|last2=Yahr|first2=Emily|title=Golden Globes nominations 2016: Complete list|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/arts-and-entertainment/wp/2015/12/10/golden-globes-nominations-2016-complete-coverage/|accessdate=10 December 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=10 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n[[File:Rosberg Massa Mexico 2015.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Williams FW37]] of [[Felipe Massa]] (front) carrying the 007 logo on its wing mirrors at the [[2015 Mexican Grand Prix]].]]\nDuring the December 2014 press conference announcing the start of filming, [[Aston Martin]] and Eon unveiled the new [[Aston Martin DB10|DB10]] as the official car for the film. The DB10 was designed in collaboration between Aston Martin and the filmmakers, with only 10 being produced especially for ''Spectre'' as a celebration of the 50th anniversary of the company's association with the franchise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.astonmartin.com/en-us/live/news/2014/12/04/built-for-bond-aston-martin-debuts-unique-car-for-spectre |title=Built for Bond: Aston Martin Debuts Unique Car for ''Spectre'' |publisher=[[Aston Martin]] |date=4 December 2014 |accessdate=4 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210005059/http://www.astonmartin.com/en-us/live/news/2014/12/04/built-for-bond-aston-martin-debuts-unique-car-for-spectre |archivedate=10 December 2014 |df= }}</ref> Only eight of those 10 were used for the film, however; the remaining two were used for promotional work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motortrend.com/news/james-bonds-spectre-10-aston-martin-db10-facts-you-need-to-know/ |title=James Bond's \"Spectre\": 10 Aston Martin DB10 Facts You Need to Know |publisher=[[Motor Trend]] |date=4 December 2015 |accessdate=4 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206144911/http://www.motortrend.com/news/james-bonds-spectre-10-aston-martin-db10-facts-you-need-to-know/ |archivedate= 6 December 2015 |df= }}</ref> After modifying the [[Jaguar C-X75]] for the film, [[Williams F1]] carried the 007 logo on [[Williams FW37|their cars]] at the [[2015 Mexican Grand Prix]], with the team playing host to the cast and crew ahead of the Mexican premiere of the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=2015 Mexican Grand Prix|work=[[Sky Sports F1]]|publisher=[[BSkyB]]|date=1 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2015/11/02/2015-mexican-grand-prix-in-pictures/wr6t0864/ |title=Felipe Massa, Williams, Autodromo Hermanos Rodriguez, 2015 |first=Keith |last=Collantine |work=F1 Fanatic |publisher=Keith Collantine |date=1 November 2015 |accessdate=2 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117024048/http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2015/11/02/2015-mexican-grand-prix-in-pictures/wr6t0864/ |archivedate=17 November 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nTo promote the film, the film's marketers continued the trend established during ''[[Skyfall]]''{{'}}s production of releasing still images of [[clapperboard]]s and [[video blogs]] on Eon's official [[social media]] accounts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/007/status/570191526476849152 |title=@007 |work=007 Official Twitter Account |date=24 February 2015 |accessdate=27 February 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220091249/https://twitter.com/007/status/570191526476849152 |archivedate=20 February 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.007.com/sam-mendes-on-spectre/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3jVnIw |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |title=Sam Mendes on Spectre |work=The Official James Bond 007 Website |date=26 February 2015 |accessdate=27 February 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> 17 brands appear in the film through [[product placement]], and many of those, such as [[Heineken]], [[Bollinger]], [[Omega SA|Omega]] and [[Sony]]\u2014owner of the film's co-distributor [[Columbia Pictures]]\u2014did ''Spectre'' tie-in advertisements.\n\nOn 13 March 2015, several members of the cast and crew, including Craig, Whishaw, Wilson and Mendes, as well as previous James Bond actor, [[Roger Moore|Sir Roger Moore]], appeared in a sketch written by [[David Walliams]] and the [[Dawson Bros.|Dawson Brothers]] for [[Comic Relief]]'s [[Red Nose Day]] on [[BBC One]]. In the sketch, they film a [[Making-of|behind-the-scenes]] [[mockumentary]] on the filming of ''Spectre''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dearden |first1=Lizzie |title=Red Nose Day 2015: Daniel Craig and Sir Roger Moore to star in James Bond Comic Relief sketch |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/red-nose-day-2015-daniel-craig-and-sir-roger-moore-to-star-in-james-bond-comic-relief-sketch-10105624.html |accessdate=13 March 2015 |work=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=13 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313231831/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/red-nose-day-2015-daniel-craig-and-sir-roger-moore-to-star-in-james-bond-comic-relief-sketch-10105624.html |archivedate=13 March 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Daniel Craig given license to thrill viewers for Red Nose Day |url=http://www.rednoseday.com/news/daniel-craig-given-license-to-thrill-viewers-red-nose-day |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315142616/http://www.rednoseday.com/news/daniel-craig-given-license-to-thrill-viewers-red-nose-day |archivedate=15 March 2015 |website=Comic Relief: Red Nose Day |accessdate=13 March 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> The first teaser trailer for ''Spectre'' was released worldwide in March 2015,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.007.com/watch-the-spectre-teaser-trailer/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3nqjJG |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |title=Watch the ''Spectre'' Teaser Trailer |work=The Official James Bond 007 Website |accessdate=19 May 2015 |date=27 March 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref><!-- Please DO NOT add details of the TV spot broadcast during the NBA Finals. Under the Manual of Style for film, this is not a particularly notable example. --> followed by the theatrical trailer in July<ref name=\"21 Jul trailer\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/22/spectre-trailer-watch-the-first-full-length-trailer-for-the-new-james-bond-film |title=''Spectre'' trailer: watch the first full-length trailer for the new James Bond film |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 July 2015 |accessdate=21 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722164051/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/22/spectre-trailer-watch-the-first-full-length-trailer-for-the-new-james-bond-film |archivedate=22 July 2015 |df= }}</ref> and the final trailer in October.<ref name=\"final trailer\">{{cite news|url=http://www.007.com/final-spectre-trailer/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3srMSv |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |title=Final ''Spectre'' trailer |work=The Official James Bond 007 Website |date=2 October 2015 |accessdate=6 October 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Daniel Craig, producer Barbara Broccoli, actress Naomie Harris and actor Christoph Waltz - Film Premiere \"Spectre\" 007 (22547549736).jpg|thumb|right|[[Daniel Craig]], producer [[Barbara Broccoli]], [[Naomie Harris]] and [[Christoph Waltz]] in a premiere for ''Spectre'' in Berlin.]]\n''Spectre'' had its world premiere in London on 26 October 2015 at the Royal Albert Hall, the same day as its general release in the United Kingdom and Republic of Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/london-lands-spectre-world-premiere-809422 |title=London Lands ''Spectre'' World Premiere |first=Alex |last=Ritman |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=17 July 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719182709/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/london-lands-spectre-world-premiere-809422 |archivedate=19 July 2015 |df= }}</ref> Following the announcement of the start of filming, [[Paramount Pictures]] brought forward the release of ''[[Mission: Impossible&nbsp;\u2013 Rogue Nation]]'' to avoid competing with ''Spectre''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paramount-shifts-mission-impossible-5-767313 |title=Paramount Shifts 'Mission: Impossible 5' Release Date to Summer 2015 |first1=Erik |last1=Hayden |first2=Pamela |last2=McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=26 January 2015 |accessdate=25 March 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150325043524/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paramount-shifts-mission-impossible-5-767313 |archivedate=25 March 2015 |df= }}</ref> In March 2015 [[IMAX]] corporation announced that ''Spectre'' would be screened in its cinemas, following ''Skyfall''{{'}}s success with the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=11712&catid=110&t=mi6&s=bond24 |title='SPECTRE' to be shown in IMAX around the world |work=Mi6-HQ |date=27 March 2015 |accessdate=21 May 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614024043/https://www.mi6-hq.com/news/index.php?itemid=11712&catid=110&t=mi6&s=bond24 |archivedate=14 June 2015 |df= }}</ref> In the UK it received a wider release than ''Skyfall'', with a minimum of 647 cinemas including 40 IMAX screens, compared to ''Skyfall''{{'}}s 587 locations and 21 IMAX screens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/spectre-box-office-uk-james-bond-daniel-craig-skyfall-1201590650/ |title='Spectre' Looms Large Over UK Box Office, But Can it Top 'Skyfall'? |author=Tartaglione, Nancy |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6q91XQyv9 |archivedate= 1 May 2017 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=23 October 2015 |accessdate=25 October 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Spectre'' was released for Digital HD on 22 January 2016 and on DVD and [[Blu-ray]] on 9 and 22 February 2016 in the US and UK respectively.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spectre BLU-RAY/DVD Info Released |url=http://www.007.com/spectre-blu-raydvd-info-released-8/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109033911/http://www.007.com/spectre-blu-raydvd-info-released-8/ |url-status=live |archivedate= 9 January 2016 |work=The Official James Bond 007 Website |date=5 January 2016 |accessdate=5 January 2016 |df= }}</ref> It debuted atop the home video charts in both countries,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/spectre-tops-home-video-sales-charts-1201708889/ |work=Variety |title='Spectre' Tops Home Video Sales Charts |first=Thomas K. |last=Arnold |date=18 February 2016 |accessdate=22 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322233002/http://variety.com/2016/digital/news/spectre-tops-home-video-sales-charts-1201708889/ |archivedate=22 March 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/james-bonds-spectre-is-the-fastest-selling-dvdblu-ray-of-2016-so-far__13958/ |author=Copsey, Rob |date=29 February 2016 |publisher=The Official Charts |title=James Bond's Spectre is the fastest-selling DVD/Blu-ray of 2016 so far |accessdate=22 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302011241/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/james-bonds-spectre-is-the-fastest-selling-dvdblu-ray-of-2016-so-far__13958/ |archivedate= 2 March 2016 |df= }}</ref> and finished 2016 with 1.5 million units in the UK, the second best-selling title of the year, behind only ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-selling-dvdsblu-rays-of-2016-revealed__17586/ |author=White, Jack |date=5 February 2017 |publisher=The Official Charts |title=The Official Top 40 biggest selling DVDs/Blu-rays of 2016 revealed |accessdate=22 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170416040647/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-selling-dvdsblu-rays-of-2016-revealed__17586/ |archivedate=16 April 2017 |df= }}</ref> and 2 million copies in the US, 12th in the year-end charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top-Selling Video Titles in the United States in 2016 |url=http://www.the-numbers.com/home-market/packaged-media-sales/2016 |publisher=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=20 March 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170129003554/http://www.the-numbers.com/home-market/packaged-media-sales/2016 |archivedate=29 January 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Spectre'' grossed $880.7 million worldwide; $135.5 million of the takings were generated from the UK market and $200.1 million from North America.<ref name=BOM /> Worldwide, this made it the [[James Bond in film|second-highest-grossing ''James Bond'' film]] after ''Skyfall'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=jamesbond.htm |title=James Bond |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=15 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160512231036/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=jamesbond.htm |archivedate=12 May 2016 |df= }}</ref> and the [[2015 in film|sixth-highest-grossing film of 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2015 |title=2015 worldwide grosses |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=15 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513173308/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2015 |archivedate=13 May 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' calculated the net profit of the film to be $98.4 million when factoring together all expenses and revenues for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/spectre-profit-box-office-2015-james-bond-1201723528/ |title=No. 16 'Spectre'&nbsp;\u2013 2015 Most Valuable Movie Blockbuster Tournament |author=Mike Fleming Jr |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=21 March 2016 |accessdate=21 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323041610/http://deadline.com/2016/03/spectre-profit-box-office-2015-james-bond-1201723528/ |archivedate=23 March 2016 |df= }}</ref> Sony had expected the net profit of the film to be around $38 million had it performed to the same level of its predecessor, but since it earned 20 percent less than ''Skyfall'', the profit in actual was $24.6 million.<ref name=\"NYTimes\"/> Sony paid 50 percent of the production costs for the film\u2014which totalled some $250 million after accounting for government incentives\u2014but received only 25 percent of certain profits, once costs were recouped. The studio also spent tens of millions of dollars in marketing and had to give MGM some of the profit from the studio's non-Bond films, including ''[[22 Jump Street]]''.<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{cite web|url=https://nytimes.com/2017/04/20/business/media/james-bond-sony-mgm-eon-productions.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qDEXEWPY |archivedate= 4 May 2017 |title=Five Studios' Mission: Winning the Distribution Rights to James Bond |author=Brooks Barnes |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 April 2017 |accessdate=21 April 2017 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn the United Kingdom, the film grossed \u00a34.1 million ($6.4 million) from its Monday preview screenings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/spectre-uk-box-office-opening-1201595185/ |title='Spectre' Shakes UK Box Office With $6.4M In Monday Previews |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028225500/http://deadline.com/2015/10/spectre-uk-box-office-opening-1201595185/ |archivedate=28 October 2015 |df= |date=29 October 2015 }}</ref> It grossed \u00a36.3 million ($9.2 million) on its opening day<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/10/spectre-uk-box-office-opening-1201595185/ |title=''Spectre'' Sets UK Box Office Record With $9.2M On Day Two |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=28 October 2015 |accessdate=29 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151028225500/http://deadline.com/2015/10/spectre-uk-box-office-opening-1201595185/ |archivedate=28 October 2015 |df= }}</ref> and then \u00a35.7 million ($8.8 million) on Wednesday, setting UK records for both days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/box-office/spectre-box-office-james-bond-1201629856/ |title=Box Office: ''Spectre'' Breaks Wednesday Record in U.K. |author=Brent Lang |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=29 October 2015 |accessdate=30 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151029214204/http://variety.com/2015/film/box-office/spectre-box-office-james-bond-1201629856/ |archivedate=29 October 2015 |df= }}</ref> In the film's first seven days it grossed \u00a341.7 million ($63.8 million), breaking the UK record for highest first-week opening, set by ''[[Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban (film)|Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban]]''{{'}}s \u00a323.9 million ($36.9 million) in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Spectre breaks UK Box Office Records: The biggest UK opening of all time |url=http://www.007.com/spectre-breaks-box-office-records/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qA3woOop |archivedate= 2 May 2017 |publisher=[[007]] |date=2 November 2015 |accessdate=6 November 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Its Friday\u2013Saturday gross was \u00a320.4 million ($31.2 million) compared to ''Skyfall''{{'}}s \u00a320.1 million ($31 million). The film also broke the record for the best per-screen opening average with $110,000, a record previously held by ''[[The Dark Knight (film)|The Dark Knight]]'' with $100,200.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-box-office-record-opening-uk-1201601884/ |title=''Spectre'' Smashes Records With $80.4M Opening |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=1 November 2015 |accessdate=1 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103154245/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-box-office-record-opening-uk-1201601884/ |archivedate= 3 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> It has grossed a total of $136.3 million there.<ref name=\"Overseas17thOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/hunger-games-mockingjay-part-2-good-dinosaur-martian-china-international-box-office-results-1201645755/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qEsAFIlf |archivedate= 5 May 2017 |title='Mockingjay' Rules Roost; 'Good Dinosaur' Hatches With $29M; 'The Martian' Lands $50M In China&nbsp;\u2013 Intl Box Office |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=29 November 2015 |accessdate=30 November 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> In the UK, it surpassed ''[[Avatar (2009 film)|Avatar]]'' to become the country's highest-grossing IMAX release ever with $10.09 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/uk-box-office-hunger-games-843123 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qEsd69Jo |archivedate= 5 May 2017 |title=U.K. Box Office: Final 'Hunger Games' on Top, 'Spectre' Sets Imax Record |author=Alex Ritman |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=25 November 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n''Spectre'' opened in Germany with $22.5 million (including previews), which included a new record for the biggest Saturday of all time,<ref name=\"Day2\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-james-bond-peanuts-movie-snoopy-maze-runner-china-international-box-office-results-1201614437/ |title='Spectre' No. 1 Everywhere It Has Opened, Pushes Gross To $290M&nbsp;\u2013 Intl B.O. Final |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=9 November 2015 |accessdate=16 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117051106/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-james-bond-peanuts-movie-snoopy-maze-runner-china-international-box-office-results-1201614437/ |archivedate=17 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> Australia with $8.7 million (including previews) and South Korea opened to $8.2 million (including previews).<ref name=\"Overseas15thOpening\"/> Despite the [[November 2015 Paris attacks|13 November Paris attacks]], which led to numerous theatres being closed down, the film opened with $14.6 million (including $2 million in previews) in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paris-attacks-spectre-prevails-france-840427 |title=Paris Attacks: 'Spectre' Prevails in France Despite Cinema Closures |author=Pamela McClintock |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=15 November 2015 |accessdate=16 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116101244/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/paris-attacks-spectre-prevails-france-840427 |archivedate=16 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> In Mexico, where part of the film was shot, it debuted with more than double that of ''Skyfall'' with $4.5 million.<ref name=\"Day2\"/> It also bested its predecessor's opening in various Nordic regions where MGM is distributing, such as in Finland ($2.7 million) and Norway ($2.9 million),<ref name=\"Day1\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-box-office-record-opening-uk-1201601884/ |title='Spectre' Smashes Records With $80.12M Opening; Bond Bow Breaks 'Skyfall' |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=1 November 2015 |access-date=16 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117063254/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-box-office-record-opening-uk-1201601884/ |archivedate=17 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> and in other markets like Denmark  ($4.2 million), the Netherlands ($3.4 million), and Sweden ($3.1 million).<ref name=\"Day1\"/> In India, it opened at No. 1 with $4.8 million which is 4% above the opening of ''Skyfall''.<ref name=\"Overseas16thOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/hunger-games-mockingjay-part-2-spectre-international-box-office-results-1201634041/ |title='Mockingjay' Lands At $144.5M As China & Caution In Europe Squeeze Hwd&nbsp;\u2013 Intl B.O. Final |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=24 November 2015 |accessdate=25 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124224450/http://deadline.com/2015/11/hunger-games-mockingjay-part-2-spectre-international-box-office-results-1201634041/ |archivedate=24 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> It topped the German-speaking Switzerland box office for four weeks and in the Netherlands, it held the No. 1 spot for seven weeks straight where it topped ''[[Minions (film)|Minions]]'' to become the top movie of the year.<ref name=\"Overseas17thOpening\"/><ref name=\"Overseas20thOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/12/mockingjay-part-2-good-dinosaur-spectre-heart-of-the-sea-point-break-star-wars-international-box-office-results-1201666009/ |title=Katniss Retakes No. 1 From China 'Surprise', 'Good Dinosaur' in 3rd, 'Sea', 007 Round Out Top 5&nbsp;\u2013 Intl Box Office Final |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=13 December 2015 |accessdate=15 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151214184946/http://deadline.com/2015/12/mockingjay-part-2-good-dinosaur-spectre-heart-of-the-sea-point-break-star-wars-international-box-office-results-1201666009/ |archivedate=14 December 2015 |df= }}</ref> The top earning markets are Germany ($70.3 million) and France ($38.8 million).<ref name=\"Overseas1stOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2016/01/sherlock-star-wars-the-force-awakens-mojin-checco-zalone-international-box-office-results-1201675349/ |title='Star Wars', Local-Language & Family Pics Lead; 'Sherlock' Shines In Korea&nbsp;\u2013 Intl B.O. |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=3 January 2016 |accessdate=4 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160104182357/http://deadline.com/2016/01/sherlock-star-wars-the-force-awakens-mojin-checco-zalone-international-box-office-results-1201675349/ |archivedate= 4 January 2016 |df= }}</ref> In Paris, it has the second-highest ticket sales of all time with 4.1 million tickets sold only behind ''[[Spider-Man 3]]'' which sold over 6.3 million tickets in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/france-box-office-star-wars-849346 |title=France Box Office: 'Star Wars' Soars In Paris on Opening Day |author=Rhonda Richford |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=16 December 2015 |accessdate=17 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220144408/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/france-box-office-star-wars-849346 |archivedate=20 December 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada the film opened on 6 November 2015, and in its opening weekend, was originally projected to gross $70\u201375 million from 3,927 screens, the widest release for a Bond film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-second-best-james-bond-opening-peanuts-movie-weekend-box-office-preview-1201604894/ |title=''Spectre'' Poised To Be Second-Best Bond Opening Of All-Time; ''Peanuts'' Coming On Strong&nbsp;\u2013 Box Office Preview |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104232050/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-second-best-james-bond-opening-peanuts-movie-weekend-box-office-preview-1201604894/ |archivedate= 4 November 2015 |df= |date=3 November 2015 }}</ref> However, after it grossed $5.3 million from its early Thursday night showings and $28 million on its opening day, weekend projections were increased to $75\u201380 million. The film ended up grossing $70.4 million in its opening weekend (about $20 million less than ''Skyfall'''s $90.6 million debut, including IMAX previews), but nevertheless finished first at the box office.<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-the-peanuts-movie-james-bond-box-office-1201610575/ |title='Spectre' $70.4M Opening: Still 2nd Highest 007 Debut Behind 'Skyfall', But Not That Far From 'Quantum Of Solace'&nbsp;\u2013 Monday AM |author=Anthony D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=9 November 2015 |accessdate=10 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108201244/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-the-peanuts-movie-james-bond-box-office-1201610575/ |archivedate= 8 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> IMAX generated $9.1 million for ''Spectre'' at 374 screens, premium large format made $8 million from 429 cinemas, reaping 11% of the film's opening, which means that ''Spectre'' earned $17.1 million (23%) of its opening weekend total in large-format venues. Cinemark XD generated $1.9 million in 112 XD locations.<ref name=\"deadline\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/08/spectre-box-office-007-scores-70m-for-second-best-james-bond-debut-weekend-ever/ |title='Spectre' Box Office: 007 Scores $70M For Second-Best James Bond Debut Weekend Ever |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=8 November 2015 |accessdate=10 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151112104519/http://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/08/spectre-box-office-007-scores-70m-for-second-best-james-bond-debut-weekend-ever/ |archivedate=12 November 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn China, it opened on 12 November and earned $15 million on its opening day, which is the second biggest 2D single day gross for a Hollywood film behind the $18.5 million opening day of ''[[Mission: Impossible&nbsp;\u2013 Rogue Nation]]'' and occupying 43% of all available screens which included $790,000 in advance night screenings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/13/spectre-box-office-007-snags-15m-opening-day-in-china-will-cross-100m-us-today/ |title='Spectre' Box Office: 007 Snags $15M Opening Day In China, Will Cross $100M In The U.S. Today |author=Scott Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=13 November 2015 |accessdate=14 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116044514/http://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/13/spectre-box-office-007-snags-15m-opening-day-in-china-will-cross-100m-us-today/ |archivedate=16 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> Through its opening weekend, it earned $48.1 million from 14,700 screens which is 198% ahead of ''Skyfall'',<ref name=\"Overseas15thOpening\"/> a new record for a Hollywood 2D opening.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4122&p=.htm |title='Spectre' Stays at #1 as It Nears $550 Million Worldwide |author=Brad Brevet |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=15 November 2015 |accessdate=16 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117015923/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4122&p=.htm |archivedate=17 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> IMAX contributed $4.6 million on 246 screens, also a new record for a three-day opening for a November release (breaking ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]''{{'}}s record).<ref name=\"Overseas15thOpening\">{{cite web\n |url=http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-prem-ratan-dhan-payo-martian-peanuts-paris-attacks-international-box-office-results-1201624317/\n |title='Spectre' Adds $152.6M In Overseas Hat Trick&nbsp;\u2013 International Box Office Update\n |author=Nancy Tartaglione\n |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]\n |date=15 November 2015\n |accessdate=16 November 2015\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116030638/http://deadline.com/2015/11/spectre-prem-ratan-dhan-payo-martian-peanuts-paris-attacks-international-box-office-results-1201624317/\n |archivedate=16 November 2015\n |df=\n}}</ref> In its second weekend, it added $12.1 million falling precipitously by 75% which is the second worst second weekend drop for any major Hollywood release in China of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chinafilminsider.com/on-screen-china-taiwans-our-times-overcomes-flame-wars-vanquishes-hunger-games/ |title=On Screen China: Taiwan's 'Our Times' Overcomes Flame Wars, Vanquishes 'Hunger Games' |author=Jonathan Papish |work=China Film Insider |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=26 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126122914/http://chinafilminsider.com/on-screen-china-taiwans-our-times-overcomes-flame-wars-vanquishes-hunger-games/ |archivedate=26 November 2015 |df= }}</ref> It grossed a total of $84.7 million there after four weekends (foreign films in the Middle Kingdom play for 30 days only, unless granted special extensions).<ref name=\"Overseas21stOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-mojin-dilwale-good-dinosaur-spectre-international-box-office-results-1201670198/ |title='Star Wars' Rules Galaxy; What Else Is Up At The International Box Office |author=Nancy Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=20 December 2015 |accessdate=21 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151221084630/https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-mojin-dilwale-good-dinosaur-spectre-international-box-office-results-1201670198/ |archivedate=21 December 2015 |df= }}</ref> Albeit a strong opening, it failed to attain the $100 million mark there as projected due to mixed response from critics and audiences as well as facing competition from local films.<ref name=\"Overseas17thOpening\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chinafilminsider.com/on-screen-china-the-martian-warms-up-a-frosty-month-for-hollywood-imports/ |title=On Screen China: 'The Martian' Warms Up a Frosty Month for Hollywood Imports |author=Jonathan Papish |work=China Film Insider |date=30 November 2015 |accessdate=1 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208035752/http://chinafilminsider.com/on-screen-china-the-martian-warms-up-a-frosty-month-for-hollywood-imports/ |archivedate= 8 December 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://chinafilminsider.com/on-screen-china-taiwans-our-times-overcomes-flame-wars-vanquishes-hunger-games/ |title=On Screen China: Taiwan's 'Our Times' Overcomes Flame Wars, Vanquishes 'Hunger Games' |author=Jonathan Papish |work=China Film Insider |date=23 November 2015 |accessdate=1 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126122914/http://chinafilminsider.com/on-screen-china-taiwans-our-times-overcomes-flame-wars-vanquishes-hunger-games/ |archivedate=26 November 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 63% based on 347 reviews, with an average rating of 6.4/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Spectre'' nudges Daniel Craig's rebooted Bond closer to the glorious, action-driven spectacle of earlier entries, although it's admittedly reliant on established 007 formula.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/spectre_2015/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028050928/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/spectre_2015 |archivedate=28 October 2016 |url-status=live |title=Spectre (2015) |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 60 out of 100, based on 48 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/spectre |title=Spectre Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106013751/http://www.metacritic.com/movie/spectre |archivedate= 6 November 2015}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2212\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref name=\"deadline\" />\n\n[[File:Dave Bautista by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|thumb|right|180px|[[Dave Bautista]] was praised for his performance as Hinx.]]\n\nPrior to its UK release, ''Spectre'' mostly received positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-34600980 |title=''Spectre'': Five-star reviews greet new Bond movie |publisher=BBC News |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=22 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022201830/http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-34600980 |archivedate=22 October 2015 |df=}}</ref> [[Mark Kermode]], writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', gave the film four out of five stars, observing that the film did not live up to the standard set by ''Skyfall'', but was able to tap into audience expectations.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kermode |first=Mark |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/oct/25/spectre-review-another-stellar-outing-for-bond-mark-kermode |title=Spectre review&nbsp;\u2013 another stellar outing for Bond |work=The Guardian |date=25 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214094923/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/oct/25/spectre-review-another-stellar-outing-for-bond-mark-kermode |archivedate=14 December 2016 |df=}}</ref> Writing in the same publication, [[Peter Bradshaw]] gave the film a full five stars, calling it \"inventive, intelligent and complex\", and singling out Craig's performance as the film's highlight.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bradshaw |first=Peter |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/oct/21/spectre-review-james-bond-is-back-stylish-camp-and-sexily-pro-snowden |title=Spectre review: James Bond is back, stylish, camp and sexily pro-Snowden |work=The Guardian |date=21 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161210034850/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/oct/21/spectre-review-james-bond-is-back-stylish-camp-and-sexily-pro-snowden |archivedate=10 December 2016 |df=}}</ref> In another five star review, ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''{{'}}s [[Robbie Collin]] described ''Spectre'' as \"a swaggering show of confidence'\", lauding it as \"a feat of pure cinematic necromancy.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Collin |first=Robbie |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/james-bond-spectre/review/ |title=SPECTRE review: 'a swaggering show of confidence' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=31 October 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151104192048/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/james-bond-spectre/review/ |archivedate= 4 November 2015 |df=}}</ref> Positive yet critical assessments included Kim Newman of ''[[Sight and Sound]]'', who wrote that \"for all its wayward plotting (including an unhelpful tie-in with Bond's childhood that makes very little sense) and off-the-peg elements, ''Spectre'' works\" as he felt \"the audience's patience gets tested by two and a half hours of set-pieces strung on one of the series' thinner plots\";<ref name=sight>{{cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/sight-sound-magazine/reviews-recommendations/film-week-spectre |title=Film of the week: Spectre |work=Sight & Sound |publisher=BFI |accessdate=31 October 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151030032903/http://www.bfi.org.uk/news-opinion/sight-sound-magazine/reviews-recommendations/film-week-spectre |archivedate=30 October 2015 |df=}}</ref> and [[IGN]]'s Chris Tilly, who rated the film 7.2 out of 10, considering ''Spectre'' \"solid if unspectacular\", and concluding that \"the film falls frustratingly short of greatness.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Tilly |first=Chris |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/22/spectre-review |title='Spectre' review&nbsp;\u2013 Solid if unspectacular Bond flick. |publisher=IGN |date=22 October 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106035657/http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/22/spectre-review |archivedate= 6 November 2015 |df=}}</ref>\n\nCritical appraisal was mixed in the United States. In a review for [[RogerEbert.com]], [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] gave ''Spectre'' 2.5 out of 4, describing it as inconsistent and unable to capitalise on its potential.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spectre Review 2015 |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/spectre-2015 |author=Matt Zoller Seitz |publisher=[[Roger Ebert.com]] |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105212614/http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/spectre-2015 |archivedate= 5 November 2015 |df=|author-link=Matt Zoller Seitz }}</ref> [[Kenneth Turan]], reviewing the film for ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', concluded that ''Spectre'' \"comes off as exhausted and uninspired\".<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite web|title=The 'Spectre' of burnout hovers over latest Bond film |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-spectre-review-20151105-column.html |author=Kenneth Turan |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106235349/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-spectre-review-20151105-column.html |archivedate= 6 November 2015 |df=|author-link=Kenneth Turan }}</ref> [[Manohla Dargis]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' criticised the film as having \"nothing surprising\" and sacrificing its originality for the sake of box office returns.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dargis |first=Manohla |authorlink=Manohla Dargis |title=Review: In 'Spectre,' Daniel Craig Is Back as James Bond, No Surprise |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=5 November 2012 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/06/movies/review-in-spectre-daniel-craig-returns-as-james-bond.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6qDEDw3Oz |archivedate= 4 May 2017 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]''' Scott Mendelson also heavily criticised the film, denouncing ''Spectre'' as \"the worst 007 movie in 30 years\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Mendelson |first=Scott |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/03/review-spectre-is-the-worst-007-movie-in-30-years/ |title=Review: 'Spectre' Is The Worst 007 Movie In 30 Years |work=[[Forbes]] |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106044322/http://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/11/03/review-spectre-is-the-worst-007-movie-in-30-years/ |archivedate= 6 November 2015 |df=}}</ref> Darren Franich of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' viewed ''Spectre'' as \"an overreaction to our current blockbuster moment\", aspiring \"to be a serialized sequel\" and proving \"itself as a Saga\". While noting that \"[n]othing that happens in ''Spectre'' holds up to even minor logical scrutiny\", he had \"come not to bury ''Spectre'', but to weirdly praise it. Because the final act of the movie is so strange, so willfully obtuse, that it deserves extra attention.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Franich |first1=Darren |title=A serious attempt to understand the ending of Spectre |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/11/10/spectre-ending |accessdate=30 November 2015 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=10 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151130203052/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/11/10/spectre-ending |archivedate=30 November 2015 |df=}}</ref> [[Christopher Orr (film critic)|Christopher Orr]], writing in ''[[The Atlantic]]'', also criticised the film, saying that ''Spectre'' \"backslides on virtually every [aspect]\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Spectre: Bond Doesn't Need an Origin Story. The 24th film in the franchise\u2014likely Daniel Craig's last\u2014dazzles early but sputters by the end. |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/11/james-bond-daniel-craig-spectre/414552/ |author=Christopher Orr |work=[[The Atlantic]] |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=7 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106165300/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2015/11/james-bond-daniel-craig-spectre/414552/ |archivedate= 6 November 2015 |df=|author-link=Christopher Orr (film critic) }}</ref> Lawrence Toppman of ''[[The Charlotte Observer]]'' called Craig's performance \"Bored, James Bored.\"<ref>{{cite news|title='Spectre' has a name: Bored, James Bored |last=Toppman |first=Lawrence |url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/ent-columns-blogs/lawrence-toppman/article42956856.html |work=[[The Charlotte Observer]] |date=5 November 2015 |page=5C |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315045227/http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/ent-columns-blogs/lawrence-toppman/article42956856.html |archivedate=15 March 2016 |df=}}</ref> Alyssa Rosenberg, writing for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', stated that the film turned into \"a disappointingly conventional ''Bond'' film.\"<ref name=\"TWPreview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/act-four/wp/2015/11/06/the-cowardly-throwback-approach-to-james-bond-in-spectre/ |title=''Spectre'' and the wasted promise of Daniel Craig's James Bond |author=Alyssa Rosenberg |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=6 November 2015 |accessdate=11 November 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110131038/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/act-four/wp/2015/11/06/the-cowardly-throwback-approach-to-james-bond-in-spectre/ |archivedate=10 November 2015 |df=}}</ref>\n\nIn a positive review published in ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] gave the film 3.5 stars out of 4, describing ''Spectre'' as \"party time for Bond fans, a fierce, funny, gorgeously produced valentine to the longest-running franchise in movies\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Travers |first=Peter |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/spectre-20151104 |title='Spectre' Movie Review |work=Rolling Stone |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106105951/http://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/spectre-20151104 |archivedate= 6 January 2016 |df=}}</ref> [[Mick LaSalle]] from the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', raved that \"One of the great satisfactions of ''Spectre'' is that, in addition to all the stirring action, and all the timely references to a secret organization out to steal everyone's personal information, we get to believe in Bond as a person.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=LaSalle |first=Mick |url=http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/James-Bond-returns-to-top-form-in-Spectre-6609518.php |title=James Bond returns to top form in 'Spectre' |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=22 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330130144/http://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/James-Bond-returns-to-top-form-in-Spectre-6609518.php |archivedate=30 March 2016 |df=}}</ref> Stephen Whitty from ''[[The New York Daily News]]'', who awarded the film four of five stars, stated that \"Craig is cruelly efficient. Dave Bautista makes a good, Oddjob-like assassin. And while Lea Seydoux doesn't leave a huge impression as this film's 'Bond girl', perhaps it's because we've already met\u2014far too briefly\u2014the hypnotic Monica Bellucci, as the first real 'Bond woman' since [[Diana Rigg]].\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Witty |first=Stephen |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/movie-review-spectre-james-bond-classic-article-1.2421805 |title=Movie review: 'Spectre' is a James Bond classic with Daniel Craig and Christoph Waltz |newspaper=The New York Daily News |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=22 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404034256/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/movie-review-spectre-james-bond-classic-article-1.2421805 |archivedate= 4 April 2016 |df=}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' film reviewer [[Richard Roeper]], who gave the film three stars out of four, considered the film \"solidly in the middle of the all-time rankings, which means it's still a slick, beautifully photographed, action-packed, international thriller with a number of wonderfully, ludicrously entertaining set pieces, a sprinkling of dry wit, myriad gorgeous women and a classic psycho-villain who is clearly out of his mind but seems to like it that way.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Roeper |first=Richard |url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/movies/spectre-review-daniel-craig-at-ease-as-an-imperfect-james-bond/ |title='SPECTRE' review: Daniel Craig at ease as an imperfect James Bond |newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times |date=3 November 2015 |accessdate=22 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406142018/http://chicago.suntimes.com/movies/spectre-review-daniel-craig-at-ease-as-an-imperfect-james-bond/ |archivedate=6 April 2016 |df= }}</ref> [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]], reviewing for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', stated, \"For all its workmanlike devotion to out-of-control helicopters, ''Spectre'' works best when everyone's on the ground, doing his or her job, driving expensive fast cars heedlessly, detonating the occasional wisecrack, enjoying themselves and their beautiful clothes.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Philips |first=Michael |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-spectre-rev-mov-20151103-column.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6q1G3EqaV |title='Spectre' review: James Bond vs. Big Brother |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=3 November 2015 |archivedate=26 April 2017 |accessdate=22 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' film critic Guy Lodge complained in his review that \"What's missing is the unexpected emotional urgency of ''Skyfall,'' as the film sustains its predecessor's nostalgia kick with a less sentimental bent.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Lodge |first=Guy |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/spectre-review-1201622685/ |title=Film Review: 'Spectre' |work=Variety |date=21 October 2015 |accessdate=22 March 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321021341/http://variety.com/2015/film/reviews/spectre-review-1201622685/ |archivedate=21 March 2016 |df=}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable 